7.2.4  France
France completed its sixth and last test in its 1995-96 Pacific test series on 
27 January 1996. This 120 Kt explosion, the largest of the series was declared 
to be the last France would ever conduct by Chirac two days later.

On 23 February 1996 Jacques Chirac announced a major restructuring of Frances 
nuclear posture. As part of dramatic overall reduction in French military 
structure (the largest in Europe), Chirac announced the elimination of all 
land-based nuclear missiles, and a halt in production of all fissile material 
for weapons. The 18 SSBS S3D MRBMs based in the Massif Central will be 
retired, as will the Hades tactical missile (now in storage). Plans are going 
forward though to upgrade the air and sea-based legs of the French nuclear 
arsenal. The submarine fleet will be re-equipped with the M51 long range 
ballistic missile, and the ASMP nuclear missile carried by the Mirage 2000N 
(and the Rafale after the turn of the century) will be upgraded.

On 4 June 1996, France and the U.S. signed an agrremetn to share data on 
nuclear weapons design. The agreement builds on 1961 and 1985 accords to share 
information on the "safety, security and reliability" of nuclear installations 
and weapons systems. Under the agreement, the United States will share 
computer data drawn from simulated explosions, information considered so 
sensitive that it has previously only been shared with the UK. The agreement 
aims to facilitate work on eight different scientific challenges posed by the 
looming global test ban, including ensuring that existing warheads remain 
potent as their components age, and preventing accidental detonation of these 
warheads or their seizure by extremists. To avoid handing over information 
that could be used to design new weapons, the U.S. decided to release the 
classified results of computer simulations that describe the workings of 
fission devices, but not the fusion stages. Since fusion energy cannot be 
released without detonating a fission trigger, safety and security issues for 
thermonuclear weapons can be adeqyuately addressed by only conisdering the 
fission primary.

Recently, for the first time, the French government has published figures on 
civilian plutonium in France. A total of 206 tonnes was held. This consists of 
55 tonnes of separated plutonium (as isolated plutonium or in fresh MOX fuel), 
nearly half of which belonged to foreign customers, and the balance in spent 
fuel. Of the latter, 64 tonnes was in spent fuel at reactors and 87 tonnes at 
reprocessing plants.

