<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>ATF, Advanced Tactical Fighter Aircraft   </TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.01Gold (Win16; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<center>
<A HREF="/milnet/acphoto/yf23side.jpg">
<img src="/milnet/acphoto/yf23side.jpg" HEIGHT=128 WIDTH=256></A>
<br>
<a href="/milnet/yf23phot.htm">Photo Library</a>
<a href="/milnet/yf23ref.htm">Reference Photo</a>
<p>
<H1>ATF, Advanced Tactical Fighter Aircraft </H1>
</center>
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<UL>
<LI>Wing span: 43.6 Ft. 43 ft 
<LI>Length: 67.4 ft. 64 ft, 2 in. 
<LI>Height: 17 ft., 8.9 in. 
<LI>Maximum Speed: Supersonic without aid of afterburner same
<LI>Range: Long range same 
<LI>Engine@Thrust: Two PW&amp; A YF119 Turbofan engines Two GE YF119 Turbofans
<LI>Armament: Aim-9 and AIM-120 AMRAAM same
<LI>carried internally 
<LI>Manufacturer: Northrop/McDonnell Douglas Lockheed/General Dynamics
</UL>

<P>The ATF was contracted to provide the next generation tactical fighter,
blending low- observable (stealth) technologies and new advances in aerodynamic
design. The down select funded two teams, the Lockheed/General Dynamics
team (<a href="/milnet/yf22ref.htm">YF-22A</a>), and the Northrop/McDonnell Douglas team (YF-32A).</P>

<P> The ATF is to be designed to penetrate enemy airspace, and support
the &quot;AirLand Battle Forces&quot; with a first-look, first kill capability
against multiple targets. With significantly integrated avionics and weapons
systems, the aircraft will be able to engage multiple targets and shoot
from a very stable platform, using internally carried AIM-9 and AMRAAM
(AIM-120) missiles, aas well as an internally mounted gun.</P>

<P> The ATF is described as being a long range, low detectability, curise
supersonic without afterburner, carry a respecable payload of air to air
missiles and still have another 1/3 power available at supersonic speeds.
The ATF must be an air superiority fighter capable of close in and stand
off operations. The ATF must be able to mount either the GE YF120 or P&amp;
WA YF119 engines, with the initial demonstraters each implementing different
engines (YF-22A will use the GE engine, the YF-23 will use the P&amp; WA
engine) to provide test beds for each. Also, the ATF must provide for 1/2
the maintenance of current fighters as well as 1/2 the sortie turnaround
time.</P>

<P> The ATF is expected to enter Full Scale Development in September of
1991 after the two demonstration aircraft define the technology base for
the final implementation, by December of 1990.</P>

<P> </P>

<H3>YF-22A</H3>

<P>The Lockheed demonstrator rolled out on August 29, 1990. Initially the
YF-22A will use General Electric YF120 engines, but both ATF will have
to be able to fitted with both the GE or the PW&amp; A engines.</P>

<P> The YF-22A has a conventional (ala F/A-18) dual canted outward vertical
stablizer at the rear, with conventional rudders. The horizontal stablizers
move fully to provide the elevator control. To control airflow on top of
the wings, there are two control panels atop each engine inlet. Most wing
and stablizer edges are all aligned in one direction to reduce the radar
signature of the aircraft. Also most openings such as canopy, gea door,
etc. have serrated edges to further aid in reduction of reflections. The
leading edge of the wing where the leading edge flap is located has strangely
shaped gaps to reduce radar cross section there as well (similiar to that
used on the F-117).</P>

<P> The aircraft is 25% manufactured of composites, with production aircraft
probably planned to be more along the lines of 40-50% composite.</P>

<P> The nozzles are located at the rear of the aircraft and can be vectored
up or down for additional thrust in those directions. There are pointed
variable flaps as part of the nozzle construction to minimize radar reflection
along the direction of flight. The engine inlets are long and provide a
curving path from their openings on either side and well forward on the
fuselage, similiar to the F-15. They are under the wing, with the engines
each inboard of the body of the fuselage, placing the high radar reflecting
portions of the engine &quot;hidden&quot; in the fuselage. This long path
is also assumed to smooth out the air flow for low distortion. The inlets
are of fixed geometry, and excess air is vented through porous inlet walls
to screened vents atop the inlet. Extra air needed for low speed, high
power conditions is provided via serrated power actuated blow-in doors
on top of the mid-fuselage.</P>

<P> There are three missile bays, one on the bottom center of the fuselage,
and two on the outside faces of the rectangular inlet walls.</P>

<P> </P>

<H3>YF-23A</H3>

<P>The YF-23A was rolled out in a low-key ceremony on June 22, 1990. It
has twin rear stabilizers canted at 45 degrees on either side of the fuselage,
and sharp chines which extend out on the forebody of the fuselage, similiar
to the extended chines on the SR-71. </P>

<P>The center section of the aircraft is also similiar to the SR-71, with
the main difference being the twin engines buried in the wings of the aircraft.
From the top, the YF-23A appears to have diamond shaped wings, and the
exhaust nozzles are obviously above the wing, probably reducing the ability
for vectored thrust (unless some kind of opening can be made through-wing).
The body of the aircraft is blended very smooth and has a flat belly where
the doors hinge into the internal stores area for the weaponry.</P>

<P> The YF-23 is a study in complex curves. But unlike the B-2 stealth
bomber, the curves are blended to provide a balance of stealth and supersonic
flight characteristics.</P>

<P> The engine inlets are under the forward oiinboard seciton of each wing,
separeed from the main forward fuselage secgtion by a deep longiudinal
channel, and feed air is ducted in through S-ducts to the engines. Two
trapazoidal panels with sawtooth aft edge are positioned on top of the
wing well forward forward of each engine inlet duct and are probably inlet
dumps or extra air intakes to be used as necessary in low or high pressure
flight regimes.</P>

<P> Visibilityin the YF-23A appears to be good, with attention being paid
to the a high mounted seat, scalloped canopy rail and forward windscreen
border, providing excellent visibility in the forward, downward, and over-the-shoulder
directions.</P>

<P> </P>

</BODY>
