<TITLE>C-130 Hercules</TITLE>
<H1>C-130 Hercules</H1>
The C-130 Hercules has been an aircraft boasting of one of the 
largest production runs of any aircraft in the Lockheed stable.  The 
uses of this aircraft were not predictable from its rather austere beginnings as a short field 
takeoff cargo aircraft in what was previously known as the Material Airlift Command.
As a MAC transport, C-130s spanned the globe 
moving cargo from San Francisco to Guam to Japan in a relentless daily effort to support at 
first the occupation of Japan and then the transistion to today's current U.S. military 
presence in that country.  C-130s had caught the eye of the Army, the U.S. Marines, the 
Army and Air Force Reserves, the National Guard, and even the Coast Guard.  Soon even 
organizations like the National Oceanographic and Atmospheric Administration were 
buying them.  One reason of course is their short landing and takeoff capability, the other is 
the fact it is such a stable aircraft, both in terms of its flyability as well as stablility of design engineering making maintenance a well known quantity, and with most every replacement part in ready availability.  The Hercules has great utility in terms of cargo caryying ability, and is quite 
economic to operate.  <P>
If you key in on another aspect of the stable platform feature, you will also understand why there are things 
such as AC-130H derivatives.  Chosen for its stability in the air, the C-130 
based AC-130H design was first used by U.S. Special Forces  
in Vietnam.  By mounting a 105mm howitzer, two 20mm Vulcan cannon and one 40mm 
cannon, you have an extremely versatile loiterable gunship called the 
"Spectre".
The original AC-130H had two 7.62mm miniguns and an extra 40mm cannon instead of the howitzer 
mounted, and was codenamed "Puff" for "Puff the Magic Dragon" (due to its visage during nightime operations, spitting fire, actually tracer rounds.  When explosive shells were used, the ground even seemed to light up, catching on fire as 
the "dragon" breathed fire down on the enemy emplacements or convoys.
<p>
Other uses include the EC-130E ABCCC (Airborne Battlefield Command and Control 
Center), the EC-130E "Volant Solo" PSYOP broadcast aircraft flown by the 193d Special 
Operations Group, the EC-130H "Compass Call" communications jammer, HC-130H 
Special Operations night vision equipped aircraf, the MC-130H "Combat Talon II" a low 
altitude penetration transport used by the 1st, 7th, and 8th Special Operations Squadrons, and the  
WC-130H weather reconaissance aircraft.  The 130s are all listed below:<P>
<UL>
<LI>C-130                MAC              		 Short field takeoff transport
<LI>AC-130A           SOF          		Gunship, 2 40mm Cannon, 2 20mm
                                        		cannon, 2 7.64 miniguns.  
                        			 Equipped with FLIR (Forward 
                         			 Looking InfraRed) sensors and 
                        			 low-light-level TV.
<LI>AC-130H           SOF          		Gunship, 1 105mm howitzer, 1 
                          			40mm cannon, and 2 20mm cannon.
                          			Equipped with interial guidance
                          			and GPS navigation equipment, 
                          			in-air refueling probe, FLIR,
                          			and low-light-level TV.

<LI>AC-130U            SOF         		 Gunship, 1 105mm howitzer, 1 
                          			40mm cannon, and 2 20mm cannon.
                        			  Equipped with interial guidance
                         			 and GPS navigation equipment, 
                         			in-air refueling probe, an 
                          			advanced fire control system,
                         			 AN/APG-180 fire control radar,
                          			FLIR, and low-light-level TV.

<LI>EC-130E              SOF, USAF   	 "Volant Solo" PSYOP broadcast
                          			equipment.

<LI>EC-130H                USAF         	"Compass Call" communications
                          			jammer equipment, operated by
                         			 the 41st Electronic Combat
                          			Squadron, Davis Monthan AFB, AZ.

<LI>HC-130H                   SOF          	Low level or night vision 
                          			equipped with communications,
                          			navigation, and countermeasures
                          			equipment.

<LI>MC-130E                    SOF         	 "Combat Talon I", low level
                          			penetration missions of the 1st,
                          			7th, and 8th SOS (Special
                          			Operations Squadrons).

<LI>MC-130H                 USAF, USMC,  	"Combat Talon II" derivative,
                                           USArmy       features explosive resistant
                          			fuel cells, in-air refueling.

<LI>WC-130H                         USAF         	Special weather radar version.
</ul>
<p>
Future Updates:
The following are systems upgrades due on the C-130 (as of 1991)
<p>
<ul>
<li>                          AWADS (Adverse Weather Aerial
                          Delivery System),
<LI>                          ESKE (Enhanced Station Keeping
                      Equipment),
<LI>                          GPWS (Ground Proximity Warning
                          System),
<LI>                          SCNS (Self Contained Navigation
                          Equipment), 
<LI>                          SOLL (Special Operations Low
                          Level) gear,
<LI>                          SVC (Secure Voice Capability).
</UL>
