<TITLE>Rockwell B-1B Strategic Penetration Bomber</TITLE>
<H2>Rockwell B-1B Strategic Penetration 
Bomber</H2>
<UL>
<LI>                                   Rockwell B-1B Strategic Penetration Bomber
<LI>Wingspan:		136ft, 8.5in. (extended), 78ft, 2.5in. fully swept	
<LI>Length:		147ft
<LI>Height:		34ft.
<LI>Weight:		477,000 lbs gross, 192,000 lbs empty
<LI>Speed:		Supersonic at Altitude, High subsonic at low penetaration altitude
<LI>Ceiling:		?
<LI>Engines:		4 
<LI>Crew:		4 (Pilot, Co-Pilot, Offensive Systems Operator, Defensive Systems Operator.
<LI>Armament:		Up to 24 B61 or B63 nuclear bombs or 12 B28 nuclear bombs, or  24 
AGM-69 
<LI>			SRAM or SRAMII attack missiles or 84 Mk52 500 lb conventional 
bombs or 
<LI>			84 Mik 36 500lb mines.  Provisions for carrying up to  12 AGM-
129A ACMor
<LI>			AGM-86B ALCM cruise missiles on six underfuselage stations but no 
current
<LI>			plans to carry cruise missiles at this time.
<LI>			
</UL>
The B-1B is a low alitutude penetration bomber designed to use terrain avoidance radar, 
high speed, and a fairly low radar cross section to rapidly sneak up on Soviet strategic 
targets.  The aircraft is designed around technology learned from the XB-70 experimental 
swept wing bomber, as well as the beginnings of stealth technology.  Although certainly not 
invisible to radar, the B-1B is never the less has only 14% of the radar signature of the B-
52G which it is intended to replace.<P>
The B-1B is able to fly at low penetration altitudes at supersonic speeds if necessary, i.e. 
this would most likely be the transition from  "stealthy" approach into the target area as  the 
B-1B accelerates from the quieter subsonic speeds to supersonic as it prepares to make its 
climb and bomb run.<P>
The B-1B, as indicated, can carry a heavy load of nuclear or conventional bombs, as well 
as the SRAM and SRAMII short range attack missile.<P>
On July 4, 1987, 2,000km close circuit speed and distance with payload record set at 
669.96 mph with 66,140 lb payload and on September 17, 5,000km circuit at 655.05 mph.  
<P>
Ther are currently 97 aircraft deployed<P>
<P>
</HTML>
