<HTML>
<TITLE>OneStep Internet Services Provider Services - Designing Your Own Home Page </TITLE>
<p><center>
                    <img src="1steplog.gif">
<p>
<p>
                                  <a href="onestep.htm"><img src="puzzle.gif"></a>


</center><H1>OneStep Internet Services Provider Services - Desigining Your Own Home Page</h1>
<p>
<p>
The design of a home page for the web can be an extremly simple process, or complex to the point of frustration.  It depends on how complex you wish to the make theentire heirarchy of pages and how "cool" you want the interface to be.  
<p>
For instance, a home page could be something as simple as a title and four "links" (underlined blue text) that lead off to four other pages.  This simple Web Server is adequate for many people.  Add in a graphic image...the home page is still quite simple and easy to understand.
<p>
But suppose you want to allow a fancy selection of the next page in the heirarchy... some eye catching navigation method to add "class" to your server.  There are a number of ways to do this, each a little more complex than the other.
<p>
<h2>Classes of Web Server</h2>
<p>
In our <a href="whitep.htm">white paper</a> we discuss a number of different goals for web servers, and how they apply to your design.  If you haven't read it yet, you might want to take a few minutes to do so.  Don't worry if you don't understand it all yet, it will become more clear as you move on.  By the way, if you see a term you don't understand, you can look at our <a href="gloss.htm">glossary</a>.
<p>
For now, however, we can simplify the types of web servers into three groups:
<ol>
<p>
<b><li>Super Complex</b> - Web Servers with large Bitmaps, Image Maps, and CGI forms based interface for moivng between pages.
<b><li>Complex</b> - Web Servers with bitmaps, graphics and a complex interconnection between pages, but usually without CGI froms or data input from the user.
<b><li>Simple</b> - Brief informational structure, with simple text and a few small grahpics, geared toward better performance on the Internet rather than flashy imagery.
</ol>
<p>
The class (1 is the highest class, 3 is the lowest) you choose will depend upon what you plan to do with your web server.  For instance a major corporation does not want to look too "stingy", thus are almost required to go for Super Complex, but still choose to goto class 2 for economical reasons.  A small business looking for a new channel for the sales of their products, may opt for a simple class three server, and then upgrade to a more fancy setup later when the web server has paid for itself.
<p>
Regardless of which class you choose, you probably want to look at our <a href="diyhome.htm">Designer Guide</a> before making the "build or buy" decision.
<p><hr>
<address>
webmaster@onestep.com
</address>
