<HTML>
<TITLE>OneStep Internet Services Provider Services - Setting Up Your Own Server</TITLE>
<p><center>
	            <img src="1steplog.gif">
<p>
<p>
 		                  <a href="onestep.htm"><img src="puzzle.gif"></a>
<p>
<img src="../undrcons.gif" alt="Under Construction"><br>
This page is intended to always be under construction so please take a look around.  There is just no other way to bring you leading edge knowlege without constantly rewriting and rephrasing. <p>

</center><H1>OneStep Internet Services Provider Services - Do It Yourself Web Server
</h1>
<p>
<ul>
<li><a href="diyunix.htm">UNIX</a> based servers
<li><a href="diynt.htm">Windows NT</a> based servers
</ul>
<p>
As you can see above, if you decide to build up your own server, you have a major software decision to make right up front.  Is it going to be UNIX or Windows NT based.  In terms of widespread knowlege in the world of the Internet, there are many more fully functional UNIX based sites out there.  But a lot of people think that Windows NT will make for easier to upgrade and maintain web servers.  <p>
In fact, Onestep has an NT server available for experimentation, and we like it a lot.  However, it seems we are always trying to figure out how to integrate the NT with our UNIX boxes while at the same time, our HD Computer's Pentium PC has a harder time talking to the NT server than the UNIX.
<p>
Actually the problems are really embedded in TCP/IP and its close links to UNIX that seem to cause all the problems...many TCP/IP packages for Windows try to look and feel familiar to X Windows/UNIX users, and some of this spreads to the actual interface.  
<p>
For instance, the interface for one of our Windows FTP utility (which works just fine with UNIX) assumes it is okay to tack on a "/" at the end of the directory it is logging into (automatically thank you very much).  While this is okay for UNIX, and while the software engineer did an excellent job of allowing us to type in a fully qualified path for this logon directory, it is a major problem for talking to NT.  Here is the sample:
<p>
<p>
<h3>UNIX</h3>
<pre>
    /var/httpd    (input by the user>

    /var/httpd/   (sent to the UNIX host at FTP logon time)
<p>
<p>
<h3>NT</h3>
<p>
   \httpd\htdocs\  (input by the user)
   \httpd\htdocs\/ (sent to the NT host at FTP log on time)
</pre>
<p>
As you can see, the interface to the user lies just a tad, and what gets sent 
to FTP is, unfortunately, worthless to NT.  The only choice for us is to ask the software manufacturer for a new version of the software with either the "/" fixed, or with an additional OS selection for NT that automatically fixes it up for us (I'd prefer that the software figure out that we're not in UNIX anymore, Toto, and change path "/"s to "\" for windows).  We won't even go into such nonsense as DOS drive letters.
<p>
In any case, despite the integration of OS problems, the other admin activities on Windows NT server may it extremely easy for a Windows knowlegeable user to maintain.  Training a 12 year old only took about 1 hour...you can forget it for most 12 year olds and UNIX.
<p>
So, make your first decision...it should be based on the availability of hardware and cost of software (oh...okay, hardware costs money too...but the same hardware can essentially be used for SCO Open Server or Windows NT).  For instance if you have a SUN lying around justing drooling over have a Web Page loaded onboard, then you choices of interface software are pretty straightforward.  If you want to try NT, don't fear, your hardware investment can be switched to SCO Open Server with little or no fuss.  
<p>
<p>
<hr>
<address>onestep@onestep.com</address>

