<p>
 		                  <a href="onestep.htm"><img src="puzzle.gif"></a>
<p>
</center><H1>OneStep Internet Services Provider Services - Do It Yourself Web Server
</h1>
<p>
So you have looked at the costs of the equipment and software, and considered that you will need someone to administer and otherwise put together all the components that go into a web server.  And after looking at that, you;ve decided maybe you can do it yourself.
<p>
To help you with this challenge are two areas within the OneStep Internet Services web space that will be emmensely helpful.  First, though, you should read the <a href="white.htm">white paper</a> (if you haven't already), to get a clear picture of how to design your web page.
<p>
Once you taken that setpe. you'll need to begin a parallel effort:
<p>
<ul>
<b><li></b>Get your hardware people working on acquiring the appropriate hardware and software.  Don't be in a rush, there is lots of used equipment perfect for the task of webbing.  
Once the hardware is located, have the admin folks begin to add the OS and install the server software.  OneStep  Internet Service scan act in several different capacities to help you through this trying period.
<b><li></b>While the hardware and OS folks are struggling with getting the PC operable, ask your software folks to get busy on storyboarding the flow of the pages.  Require frequent reviews of all the sections of the target web space,  and ensure thee is a good logical flow.  When you finally "buy-off" on the storyboards, then and only then should work begin on the HTML and images necessary for your web space.
<b><li></b>A word about CGI and Imagemaps.  If your Web Space is of the highly complex variety taking full advantage of CGI scripts and Imagemaps, then some additional planning and coordination will need to take place.  This is an extremely sensitive servef security area, as well as fraught with "thrashing" type errors until you get it up and running.  Again, we suggest a professional, like ourselves, to help you through this effort.
</ul>
<p>
<p>
