<html
<title>MILNET:  Travel Advisories - Mirror Copy - India</title>
<center>
<p>
<a href="/milnet/milnet.htm"><img src="/milnet/milico.gif" align=middle alt="Mil
net Main"></a>
<a href="/milnet/terror.htm"><img src="/milnet/terror.gif" align=middle alt="Ter
rorism"></a>
<p>
<h1>India</h1>
<hr>
<p>
<h2>STATE DEPARTMENT TRAVEL INFORMATION
</h2>
</center>
<hr>
<p>
<b>Jammu &amp; Kashmir - Public Announcement</b><br>
May 17, 1996<p>

 U.S. DEPARTMENT OF STATE<br>
 Office of the Spokesman<br>
 For Immediate Release<p>

As the summer tourist season approaches, the Department of State again strongly urges private
U.S. citizens traveling in India to avoid travel to Jammu and Kashmir, in particular the cities of
Jammu, Srinagar, the Kashmir Valley and surrounding mountains.  Terrorist activities, including
bombings, assassinations, kidnappings, and violent civil disturbances, have occurred in these
areas.  Kidnapping is a particularly strong danger to U.S. citizens and other foreigners in Kashmir. 
There have been bombings attributed to Kashmiri militants as well as armed clashes between
militants and Indian security forces.  While U.S. citizens and other foreigners have not been
targeted in these incidents, some bombings have occurred in public places where foreign visitors
might congregate.<p>

Militants have threatened to use violence to disrupt May 23 and May 30 elections in Kashmir and
Indian security forces are on heightened alert.  There is a possibility of increased violence,
including attacks on airlines and other modes of public transport or other facilities, which could
affect innocent bystanders even after the elections have taken place.<p>

The U.S. Embassy in New Delhi prohibits U.S. government employees from traveling to the
Jammu and Kashmir areas without U.S. Embassy permission.<p>

U.S. citizens in India may wish to contact the U.S. Embassy in New Delhi for updated security
information.  The U.S. Embassy telephone number is (91)(11)688-9033.<p>
No. 96-india<P>
This replaces the previous public announcement of August 17, 1995 to update information on the
dangers of travel by U.S. citizens to Jammu and Kashmir and to provide the new telephone
number for the U.S. Embassy in New Delhi.<p>
<p>
