<title>MILNET:  Travel Advisories - Mirror Copy - Peru</title>
<center>
<p>
<a href="/milnet/milnet.htm"><img src="/milnet/milico.gif" align=middle alt="Mil
net Main"></a>
<a href="/milnet/terror.htm"><img src="/milnet/terror.gif" align=middle alt="Ter
rorism"></a>
<p>
<h1>Peru</h1>
<hr>
<p>
<h2>STATE DEPARTMENT TRAVEL INFORMATION
</h2>
</center>
<hr>
<b>Peru - Public Announcement</b><br>
 August 23, 1996<br>
<p>
U.S. DEPARTMENT OF STATE<br>
Office of the Spokesman<br>
<p>

On August 23, the American Embassy in Lima issued the following 
notice to American citizens in Peru:
<p>
"The Embassy has received information that Aero Continente Airlines 
has been operating aircraft with unsafe engine conditions.  It is 
our opinion that this constitutes an unacceptable risk to U.S. 
Embassy employees.
<p>
Therefore, all U.S. Mission personnel are hereby prohibited from 
flying Aero Continente until further notice."
<p>
The State Department is making this information available to the 
public.  Further, the U.S. Embassy has informed the government of 
Peru of its concerns and has received assurances that immediate 
action is being taken to ground aircraft with unsafe engines and 
review airline procedures and practices to ensure the proper 
maintenance and safety of all Aero Continente aircraft.  Competent 
international aviation authorities and equipment suppliers are 
providing technical assistance to correct this problem.
<p>
For further information on travel to Peru, consult the Department 
of State's latest Consular Information Sheet for Peru.
<p>
