<title>MILNET:  Travel Advisories - Mirror Copy - Sauid Arabia</title>
<center>
<p>
<a href="/milnet/milnet.htm"><img src="/milnet/milico.gif" align=middle alt="Mil
net Main"></a>
<a href="/milnet/terror.htm"><img src="/milnet/terror.gif" align=middle alt="Ter
rorism"></a>
<p>
<h1>Sauid Arabia</h1>
<hr>
<p>
STATE DEPARTMENT TRAVEL INFORMATION - Saudi Arabia
</center>
<hr>
<p>
Saudi Arabia - Public Announcement<br>
 July 10, 1996<br>
<p>
 U.S. DEPARTMENT OF STATE<br>
 Office of the Spokesman<br>
 For Immediate Release<br>
<p>
On July 10, 1996, the American Embassy in Riyadh, Saudi Arabia,
issued the following warden message to U.S. citizens in Saudi Arabia:
<p>
"The U.S. Embassy and other elements of the U.S. government in
Saudi Arabia continue to assist Saudi authorities in their
investigation of the June 25 bombing and their effort to apprehend
those responsible for this tragedy, wherever they may be.  We
continue to work with the Saudis to implement additional measures
designed to protect the security of Americans in the Kingdom.
<p>
Unfortunately, the sophistication of the operation behind the June
25 bombing suggests that additional attacks are quite possible.  The
U.S. Embassy continues to receive reports that suggest that there
could be further attacks upon official and unofficial U.S.
facilities, as well as other facilities that employ or are
frequented by U.S. and foreign citizens.  In addition, individual
Americans and companies in Saudi Arabia have received calls
threatening further attacks.  Some of these reports may have no
basis or be only harassment.  But it is likely that some of these
reports reflect planning for attacks.

<p>
As a result, the U.S. Embassy wishes again to remind the entire
American community of the importance of exercising extreme caution,
keeping a low profile, reducing travel within the Kingdom, and
treating mail from unfamiliar sources with suspicion.  U.S.
facilities are at very high states of alert and we continue to
stress that all Americans in Saudi Arabia should be especially
vigilant of their personal security and surroundings, paying
particular attention to suspicious vehicles.  Any suspicious
activity or vehicles should be quickly reported to the nearest
embassy or consulate.  License numbers and full descriptions will be
invaluable.
<p>
The U.S. Embassy will endeavor to keep the community informed of
relevant security information through the warden system.  To access
the system within Saudi Arabia, call 488-3800 and press 7."
<p>
 No. 96-sa10
<p>
