<TITLE>MILNET:  Military Information - Saudi Arabia </TITLE>
<center>
<img src="milnetsm.gif" align=middle, alt="Milnet">
<p>
<p>
<a href="milnet.htm"><img src="milico.gif" align=middle alt="Milnet Main"></a>
<a href="military.htm"><img src="miltico.gif" align=middle alt="Military"></a>
<p>
<p></center>
<H1>Saudi Arabia </H1>
<p>
This large mid-Eastern country enjoys the benefit of many years of 
arms accumulation encompassing purchases from both pro-western sellers 
as well as pro-soviet.  The Saudi (male only) is concripted into the 
military between the ages of 18 to 35, with a total in arms of 
approximately 51,500 (.429 % of their 12 million population). 
<p>
It should be noted that at the conclusion of the Gulf War, much of the 
allied armor and other heavy equipment was left in the region.  It is 
expected that a goodly number of main battle tanks, artillery, and other
major war waging weapons were sold in place to Saudi Arabia, Egypt, and/or Kuwait
probably in turn for secret supplies of oil or other concessions.  This 
information is based upon speculation, however, tonnage coming home 
greatly mismatched that one would expect from spent munitions and supplies.
<P>
<B>Total Armed Forces: </B> 51,500<P>
<B>Total defense budget( 1983)</B>:  $22 billion out of a $153 billion 
Gross Domestic Product (14.379% GDP to defense).
<P>
The following is a list of the weapons known to be owned by the Saudis 
as of 1/1/86:<P>
<H2>Army:  </H2><pre>
  35,000 men
           3 Armored Brigades, with 1 forming
