<TITLE>Jordan</TITLE>
<center>
<img src="milnetsm.gif" align=middle, alt="Milnet">
<p>
<p>
<a href="milnet.htm"><img src="milico.gif" align=middle alt="Milnet Main"></a>
<a href="military.htm"><img src="miltico.gif" align=middle alt="Military"></a>
<p>
<H1>Jordan (data from 12/84)</H1>
</center>
The British 1922 mandate included the lands now called Jordon.  In 1921, Abdullah the son of the ruler of Hejaz in Arabia was 
installed by Britain as the emir of an autonomous Transjordan, coering two-thirds of Palestine.  An independent kingdom was 
proclaimed in 1946.  <BR>
	The West Bank and the old city of Jerusalem were added to the kingdom in 1948 as part of land grabs at the end of 
the Arab-Israeli war of 1948 and this new country became Jordan.<BR>
	In the 1967 Yom Kippur war, all these lands added were taken back by  Israel  and Jordon became a site for 
Palestinian refugees.<BR>
	During the weeks before the  Iraq-Kuwait  War, refugees once again streamed into Jordon, fleeing the oppressive 
rule of Suddam Hussein of Iraq.  Finally Jordon had to close her borders as there was no room in the refugee camps.  Later in 
the war, King Hussien of Jordon threw his verbal support to Iraq, and this mistake will undoubtedly not bode well for Jordan in 
the resolution of the Middle East conflicts in the years to come.  See also  Statistics  and  MidEast: Pro-Soviet .<P>
<img src="/milnet/note!sm.gif" align=middle>
The data below was verified in 1984.  Obviously it is obsolete.  We include
it here, however, as a measure of the forces available at that time.
We will endeavor to update that information as soon as we can given our
other goals for MILNET.
<p>

<H4>Total Armed Forces:  76,300<BR>
Total Defense Budget in 1984:  $541,755 million</H4>
<P>
<B>Army: </B> 68,000<BR>
6 armd bdes.<BR>
4 mech bdes<BR>
1 indep. Royal Guards bde<BR>
1 Special Forces bde<BR>
