<TITLE>Lebanon</TITLE>
<center>
<img src="milnetsm.gif" align=middle, alt="Milnet">
<p>
<p>
<a href="milnet.htm"><img src="milico.gif" align=middle alt="Milnet Main"></a>
<a href="military.htm"><img src="miltico.gif" align=middle alt="Military"></a>
<p>
<H1>Lebanon</H1>
</center>

Lebanon is located along the eastern coast of the Mediterannean, north of Israel.  The city of Beirut, once a beautiful tourist 
attraction with wide, beautiful beaches, is now a burned out shell, with gun fights erupting daily between the various factions of 
Christian, Kurdish, and Muslim factions.  The southern parts of the country serves as staging areas for various anti-Israel 
factions incursions into Israeli territory.  The U.S. has a bloody history in Lebanon, when as part of U.N. and unilateral  efforts 
to stem the incursions into Israel and support a more favorable Leganese government, 103 marines were killed in a truck bomb 
attack on their barracks.  A similar attack on the U.S. embassy also killed many Americans, and the U.S. pulled out.  Not after, 
however, retalitating by pounding the city of Beirut and the hillsides with shells from the U.S. Missouri's huge guns.<P>
<img src="/milnet/note!sm.gif" align=middle>
The data below was verified in 1984.  Obviously it is obsolete.  We include
it here, however, as a measure of the forces available at that time.
We will endeavor to update that information as soon as we can given our
other goals for MILNET.
<p>

