<HTML>
<title>Libya</title><P>
<center>
<img src="milnetsm.gif" align=middle, alt="Milnet">
<p>
<p>
<a href="milnet.htm"><img src="milico.gif" align=middle alt="Milnet Main"></a>
<a href="military.htm"><img src="miltico.gif" align=middle alt="Military"></a>
<p>
<H1>Libya</H1>
</center>
<P>
Libya is poised at the northern edge of North Africia, and is situated just across the Mediterranean Sea from Italy, Sicily and 
Greece.  It is almost as large as Saudi Arabia and has a population of around 3.5 million people.<P>
Libya is ruled by Mohamar Quaddafi (spelling disputed), a charismatic leader who has brought the many moslem tribes together in his country, rules with 
an iron hand, but remains the people's hero.  A seemingly devout Moslem, he appears to be a firm believer in the Jihad, the holy war against infidels, with the Western Nations being his nemesis.
<p>
In the middle of Ronald Reagan's administration, the U.S. accussed Libya of fostering terrorism.  U.S. warships entered the Gulf of Sidra to provoke Quaddafi, 
who obliged by sending out aircraft, which were promptly outclassed and shot 
down.  
<p>
When a the frequent hangout for
U.S. Servicemen was bombed, killing several U.S. servicemen, the U.S. released information linking Libya to the 
group claiming responsibility, and arranged for a retalitory strike.
<p>
F-111 fighter bombers originating in the U.K. and refueled in route, bombed 
a barracks where Quaddaffi and his staff were purported to be, as well as key
command and control emplacements.  Quaddafi was not hurt and continues today
a bit more empowered than before due to his survival.
<p>
However, Libya's ties with terrorism and indeed the Libyan rhetoric has 
completely vanished from public view.  The only public view of Quaddafi since
the U.S. attack, was his appearance with Suddam Hussien during the Gulf War where
he pledged (but never delivered) to support Iraq against the U.S. led U.N.
coalition.  Below we list the forces estimated in Libya in 1984, much of which 
remains the same today except where noted:
<p>
<P>
<img src="/milnet/note!sm.gif" align=middle>
The data below was verified in 1984.  Obviously it is obsolete.  We include
it here, however, as a measure of the forces available at that time.
We will endeavor to update that information as soon as we can given our
other goals for MILNET.
<p>

<B>Total Armed Forces:  73,000</B><br>
<B>Estimated Defense Budget:  $709.22 (1982)</B><P>
<b>Army Forces:  58,000</b><br>
1 Tk and 1 mech inf div HQ<BR>
20 tk bns.<BR>
30 mech inf bns.<BR>
1 National Guard bn.<BR>
