<html>
<title>MILNET: Military Information:  Japan</title>
<p>
<center>
<img align=middle src="milnetsm.gif">
<p>
<a href="milnet.htm"><img alt="Milnet Main" align=middle src="milico.gif"></a>
<a href="intell.htm"><img alt="Intell" align=middle src="intell.gif"></a>
<p>
<h1>Japan</h1>
</center>
<hr>


An island of some 123 million inhabitants, Japan  is a major link in the strategic control of the eastern shores of the Soviet Union.   With U.S. bases at a number of choke points, and the 245,000 strong Japan Defense Forces, the island nation provides the U.S. with the ability to control the seasoff the Soviet Union if it becomes necessary.
<p>
The U.S. protection is part of a treaty signed in 1960, which on one hand limited the number of Japanese forces allowable after World War II, as well as defines the comittment the U.S. makes.  
<p>
But in order to aid the U.S. in the coverage of this strategic area in the Pacific, Japan has slowly been growing the Japan Defense Forces.
<p>
<img src="/milnet/note!sm.gif" align=middle>
The data below was verified in 1985.  Obviously it is obsolete.  We include
it here, however, as a measure of the forces available at that time.
We will endeavor to update that information as soon as we can given our
other goals for MILNET.
<p>

The Japanese Self Defense Forces are divided into three uniformed services
<p>
<ul>
<li>Air Self Defense Force (<a href="/milnet/asdf.htm">ASDF</a>)
<li>Marine Self Defense Force (<a href="/milnet/msdf.htm">MSDF</a>)
<li>Ground Self Defense Force (<a href="/milnet/gsdf.htm">GSDF</a>)
</ul>
<p>
Note:  Since the breakup of the Soviet Union, Japan's strategic role is somewhat lessened in the eyes of the U.S., and may effect U.S. funding.
<p>
<hr>
Last Updated:  12/1/86
</html>

