<html>
<title>MILNET</title>
<center>
<h1>MILNET</h1>
</center>
<hr>
The document you have requested is undergoing an update, with the 
date for completion unknown at this time.  We apologize for the
inconvience, but as the data was most likely only current as of
1984, we felt it necessary to remove either portions of the data
or the page in its entirity, pending this update.
<p>
<h1>North Korean Incursion Into South Korea</h1>
<p>
Mid way thorugh the year in 1950, a small contingent of U.S. troops in South 
Korea reported alarming movements of North Korean forces near the line 
separating the two countries.  A failure to respond to these movements by 
U.N. and specifically U.S. forces stationed in South Korea (primarily a higher
echelon failing, certiainly not on the part of ground commanders), resulted in
the North Korean invasion of South Korea taking place without plenty of 
resistance, but with little force to stop them.
<p>
However, in a weeks time, the U.N. (specifically U.S.) forces began to
arrive in nearly sufficient numbers as to build a front.  By August of
1950, U.S. Air Commandos were dropping supplies for friendly agents into North Korea
in an effort to build intelligence networks to combat the invading rush.
<p>
U.S. Armored Divisions began to move, and by the end of August, a fully operational
war front was established.
<p>
The resolution of the war was a return to status quo, with both North and South
Korea once again respecting their separating line.  Today, the two countries
remain divided, with saber rattling and an occasional border incident keeping
the two nations at each other's throats diplomatically.  
<p>
One of the most alarming events in the recent past has been the North 
Korean refusal to observe the tenants of the Non-Proliferation Treaty, thus
acting as if they were going to begin production of nuclear weapons.  While 
the noise on this subject has died down, it is clear there is a major desire
for the North Koreans to move into the fraternity of nuclear nations, and 
thus presents a new class of problems to both South Korea, and its chief 
guardian, the United States.  
  
<hr>
<a href="mailto:milnet@onestep.com"><i>milnet@onestep.com</i></a><br>
