<HTML>
EX-U.S. MILITARY OFFICERS ASSIST CROAT ARMY By LOUIS J. SALOME<P>
Cox News Service<P>
ZAGREB, Croatia -- Former U.S. military personnel, working in secret near Zagreb, are teaching the 
expanding Croat armed forces western methods of military organization, management and discipline.<P>
About 15 Americans, employed by Military Professional Resources Inc. (MPRI) of Alexandria, Va., have 
been instructing the Croats since mid-November. They arrived in the explosive region two months after 
the firm, which employs about 120 retired and former U.S. military personnel, and the Croat 
government signed a contract with the blessing of the State Department.<P>
Retired U.S. Army Lt. Gen. Ed Soyster, MPRI's vice president for international operations, said in a 
telephone interview that employees of the seven-year-old company are teaching Croat forces how to 
function in a democratic society.<P>
Soyster, director of the super-secret U.S. Defense Intelligence Agency from December 1988 until 
September 1991, said MPRI is not providing Croatia with intelligence information and has no 
intelligence contracts. Soyster said he is the only former intelligence officer at MPRI.<P>
Both Soyster and U.S. officials in Zagreb denied that MPRI is offering military training or teaching 
military tactics. To do so, Soyster said, would violate the international embargo against military 
equipment or services reaching Croatia.<P>
Despite the embargo, Croatia has in the past couple of years bought or been given large quantities of new 
weapons, most of which are believed to have come from former eastern bloc countries.<P>
Newspaper reports published in the Balkans in May said that 30 up-to-date Russian MiG-29 jet fighters, 
bought from the Czech Republic, were about to be added to Croatia's arsenal.<P>
The MPRI-Zagreb arrangement, sanctioned by the State Department, reflects the growing U.S. influence 
in Croatia. U.S. diplomats have ready access to Croat leaders and the Pentagon has signed a military 
agreement that would allow Croats to study at U.S. military bases and schools. Congress has not yet 
approved the deal.<P>
Although there is widespread skepticism in the region that U.S. assistance is limited to helping Croatia's 
military adjust to democracy, Soyster said, ``There is nothing lethal that we teach. We don't teach use of 
weapons because we'd lose our (State Department) license if we did that.''<P>
Soyster said MPRI has a ``long-term contract'' with Croatia. But he refused to reveal its length, the 
amount of money involved or exactly where in Croatia MPRI instructors are teaching.<P>
U.S. officials in Zagreb referred all questions about the contract to MPRI, and Croat officials refused to 
answer questions about the arrangement.<P>
Soyster said MPRI is helping Croatia develop a chain of command for non-commissioned officers. He 
said it is also teaching the Croat armed services new budgeting, management, planning and program 
techniques, helping them draw the distinction between military and civilian law, and instructing them 
on how to act toward civilians during and after a battle.<P>
``We're not teaching tactics or combined military operations,'' Soyster said.<P>
Most of MPRI's employees are former officers, Soyster said. But, he said, two of its employees working in 
Croatia are retired sergeant-majors who are assisting Croatia in developing its non-commissioned 
officers' corps.<P>
The Croat army was widely criticized for human rights abuses against civilians among ethnic Krajina 
Serbs during Croatia's war of secession from the former Yugoslavia in 1991, which Serbia and the 
Krajina Serbs resisted.<P>
But Croatia's successful offensive in early May against the Krajina Serbs in an area known as western 
Slavonia appears to have been marked by fewer human rights abuses against civilians than would have 
been expected 12 months ago. In Croatia, the relative change is widely attributed to American training 
and to the additional weapons Croatia has acquired since 1991.<P>
``The principles we're teaching certainly parallel where they want to go and what the Croats did in 
western Slavonia,'' Soyster said. ``We're good, but we're not into what happened in the Krajina area or 
that sort of thing. We don't have a contract to do that and we're not doing it.''<P>
Croatia's offensive was quick, unexpected and well-coordinated on the ground and in the air. Croat police 
moved in quickly to take control of the area and protect civilians after the military had taken the 
area.<P>
Since last fall, MPRI has had a contract directly with the State Department to provide monitors who 
assist the Geneva-based International Conference on the Former Yugoslavia. The monitors work along 
the Bosnia-Serbia border.<P>
Soyster said that contract was a ``short-term one,'' but a State Department official in Washington called 
the contract ``open-ended.''<P>
The State Department official, who asked not to be identified, said in a telephone interview that MPRI 
provides up to 50 monitors at one time to watch for military trucks or equipment crossing into Bosnia 
from Serbia.<P>
When the monitoring began late last summer, U.S. foreign service officers were posted on the border to 
report to the International Conference on the Former Yugoslavia. But they proved insufficient to handle 
the job, so the State Department engaged MPRI, the State Department official said.<P>
