<center>
<h1>MILNET:  Reconnaissance Aircraft</h1>
<hr>
</center><P>
Reconnaissance Aircraft comprise a multitude of differing
platforms and missions.  For reconnaissance has grown from the
simple film based overflights with ballons of World War I, to
the exotic aircraft such as the  SR-71  which flies above 80,000
feet and at speeds greater than Mach 3.
<P>
The following is a list of U.S. Recon Aircraft which are in
service today.  The SR-71 listing is included for completeness
despite the fact this incredible aircraft was retired in 1990
after 30 years of nearly flawless and as of yet unmatched aeronautical
performance.  For further information on U.S. Aircraft, see also
 U.S. Aircraft .
<P>
<pre>
<b>Designation Manufacturer Agency  Description/Mission
</b>
<P>
U2/TR-1  Lockheed USAF/CIA High alt. Strategic Recon aircraft,
film, ELINT,
<P>
      COMINT, etc.
<P>
SR-71   Lockheed USAF  High Speed, High Altitude Recon (Retired)
<P>
E-3B/C  Boeing/Westing. USAF  Airborne Warning And Control
System (AWACS)
<P>
      providing airborne C3I capabilities and tactical
<P>
      tracking and intercept control.
<P>
E-4B  Boeing/Rockwell USAF  National Emergency Airborne Command
Post
<P>
      (NEACP).
<P>
RF-4C  McDonnel Douglas USAF  Day-Night all weather tactical
recon, RADINT
<P>
      COMINT, ELINT, etc.
<P>
E-8A  Boeing/Grumman USAF/USA/USN Joint Surveillance and Target
Attack Radar System
<P>
      (JSTARS), look down capability onto the battlefield

<P>
      combined with data links to artillery and other assets
<P>
      which can then attack opponents as they move 
<P>
      about the battlefield.
<P>
EC-18B/D Boeing  USAF  Advanced Range Instrumentation Aircraft
(ARIA)
<P>
      range instrumentation for NASA and military 
<P>
      missiles launches, and a new mission under
<P>
      development, monitoring and controlling UAVs.
<P>
EF-111A  General Dynamics USAF  Defense Suppression (Anti-Radiation,
Jamming,
<P>
      etc.)
<P>
F-117A   Lockheed USAF  Stealth Fighter (Stealthy Recon Capable)
<P>
EC-130  Lockheed USAF  Airborne Command and Control Center
<P>
EC-135  Boeing/Rockwell USAF  Airborne Command Post (Looking
Glass), Airborne
<P>
      Launch Control System (ALCS),  Post Attack 
<P>
      Command and Control System (PACCS).
<P>
RC-135   Boeing/Rockwell USAF  Strategic Air Command, Recon
and special EW
</BODY>

