<TITLE>OneStep Internet Services Provider Services - WWW Glossary</TITLE>
<p><center>
                    <img src="1steplog.gif">
<p>
<p>
                                  <a href="onestep.htm"><img src="puzzle.gif"></a>



</center><H1>OneStep Internet Services Provider Services - WWW Glossary</h1>
<p>
<p>
The following glossary presents brief explanations for commonly used terms in the use and development of WorldWide Web servers.
<p>
<dl compact>
<b><dt>WWW</b>
<dd><b>World Wide Web</b>, the core system for the graphical presentation of information over the Internet.  Servers are linked via the Internet to users who request data from the servers, and in some cases may input data (ordering information or simply comments).
<p>
<b><dt>Web Servers</b>
<dd>A Web Server is a series of pages stored on the host computer where different "Information Providers" place the information viewed by users.  But don't confuse Web Server with host computer (sometimes the two are in essence the same entity, but not always...for instance, the host computer the OneStep Internet Services Web Server is residing on actually is the home for many different home pages and thus appears to be a virtual web server).
<p>
<b><dt>Host Computer</b>
<dd>This terminology comes from the development of the client/server model of computing, where a server provides services to clients (users) upon request.  A Web Server providese information when the user makes a request while using an application on their PC, X Terminal, or Workstation.  The application in this case is the client, and the server is the host computer.
<p>
<b><dt>Home Page</b> 
<dd>The home page is nothing more than the first page for a particular Web Server area...i.e. the first page of the OneStep Internet Services web server.  A home page usually servers as the top layer in a heirarchy of lower level pages, each which allow the user to move down into different categories of interest before arriving at the actual information they wish to see.  Remember, multiple home pages can reside on a single host computer.
<p>
<b><dt>Browser</b>
<dd>A web Browser is nothing more than a special application which allows end users to view the Home Page and any pages below it in the web server's heirarchy.  For instance, the page you are reading has been formatted by your browser so you see some indented descriptions that make up this glossary.
To see what this "page" really looks like, look at the file or edit menu to find the "View Source" option.   This will display the "HTML" encoded text which the browser program must interpret.
<p>
<b><dt>HTML</b>
<dd><b>Heiarchical Text Markup Language</b>.  This is the standard method for using symbols such as <b>;lt&ADDRESS;lt&/a></b> to indicate how a particular web page should be formatted.  Formatting can include bold or italicized text, adding header test of various sizes, or the formatting that creates this indented list you are now reading.
</dl>
<p>
<hr>
<address>webmaster@onestep.com</address>
</html>

