<TITLE>OneStep Internet Services Provider Services - Do Your Own UNIX</TITLE>
<p><center>
	            <img src="1steplog.gif">
<p>
<p>
 		                  <a href="onestep.htm"><img src="puzzle.gif"></a>
<p>
<img src="../undrcons.gif" alt="Under Construction">  Current Update:  6/20/95<br>
This page is intended to always be under construction so please don't be put off by seeing the unders construction signs.  There is just no other way to bring you leading edge knowlege without constantly modifying the material. <p>

</center><H1>OneStep Internet Services Provider Services - Do Your Own UNIX 
</h1>
<p>
Okay, good decision (if you look at the NT branch, we say the same thing...either choice is good).  If you choose a SUN OS platform, you should immediately start looking at the public domain <a href="http://hoohoo.ncsa.uiuc.edu/">Httpd</a> source code available.  There will probably be ready to roll executable code availabe as well.  In fact, the SUN environment is well understood on the Internet. If you want some info on commercially supported software for SUN or SGI platforms, there are a few web pages that will help in the the <a href="http://www.yahoo.com/Computers/world_wide_web/HTTP/Servers/Platforms/">Yahoo</a> collection. 
<p>
If you are looking at a very low cost approach, then you might consider using SCO Open Enterprise servers.  This is one of the approaches we have tried (actually was are NT, SUN OS, and SCO capable).  If you choose SCO, there are a number of special considerations you must make...Here is what you need to price before finalizing your decision.
<ul>
<b><li></b>486, 33Mhz minimum (don't buy a Pentium if you are using 14.400 baud and PPP...a 486 will stay ahead of the datacomm, no problem!), 
16MB RAM (more is better), 200MB disk space (more is better).  If you're installiing NT or SCO, you only really need a 640X480 VGA card, but higher res is more fun.  
Obviously your monitor should match your VGA card.
We recommend you go SCSI interface for Disks and CDROMs...it costs more but allows you more flexibility as you grow your server requirements (moving a SCSI disk to a new system is easier than any other).
<p>
You'll need a SCSI tape drive (set to SCSI address #2) to load SCO Open Server.  Version 3.0 is quite acceptable.  If you find a good deal on 
an older version, don't take it. The older versions run okay, but it is far to easy to screw up the instalation to the point you will never get your httpd server running.  Plus, 3.0 has some basic installation features that make it so much easier to install without screwing up.
<p>
<b><li></b>You should buy yourself a 16 bit or better NE2000 compatible network card.  We recommend this cuz the NE2000 compatibles easily transport across all OS and hardware environments in the Intel based server world.  The card will offer you great utility for years.
<p>
<b><li></b>For http software (that's the server software that makes web pages available over the Internet), you really have to buy it from SCO if you're using OPen Server.  Fortunately, the "Global Access" server product is acceptable, and is only around $150.  SCO Open Desktop may appear to be more expensive than say Microsft NT, but it is loaded with TCP/IP features, making it a good buy for any kind of expansion later on . 
<p>
Now a word to our friends visiting from NT land. Much of the Internet is implemented in UNIX environments.  Certainly the networking is TCP/IP expert land at the least.  So when we start talking about building UNIX systems for Web Servers,
we are going to relate to the UNIX and TCP/IP audience.  You Windows gurus will just have to ignore the UNIX and TCP/IP rhetoric as best as you can.<p>
<p>
Installing SCO Open Server 3.0 is actually quite easy.  In fact, so easy, that we will only list those things you need to have handy before you start...
<ol>
<b><li></b>
Initial load  - Chunk in the tape (150MB QIK-150 format), and boot the machine.
<b><li></b>If your SCSI card wasn't in the list from the installation guide, you may need to learn how to change it to the correct SCSI info via the "Boot" string method.
<b><li></b>If necessary you may to slip in the SCSI driver disk and go through 
the disk.  
<b><li></b>
You'll need your domain name, i.e. yourdomain.com, your assigned IP address, and most importantly have the installation serial number and activiation key close by, SCO won't as for this until after the lion share of the installation is done, and not having it ready to enter into the appropriate place  may mean you have to reload the whole system.
<b><li></b>
SCO Open Server installation will ask a number of questions up front, almost eliminating the need to answer any further questions later on during the installation.  
<b><li></b>
Choose all the installation options with Open Server 3.0.  But if you decide to try to limit the amount of disk space used, you really only need the basic system plus the networking options.
<b><li></b>Once the tape draw completes, the actual installation script will run.  
<b><li></b>
<b><li></b>Eventually you are asked to reboot the system.  Things get interesting again.
</ol>
<p>
<p>
<h2>
Installing Mail, NFS, and NIS</h2>
<p>
Before installing the Global Access package, you'll want to install Mail, NFS, and NIS.  This prepares the system for upgrades in these three areas during the Global Access installation.  Follow the Open Server Installation and Release Notes to make these changes easy.  You might look into purchasing the Open Server Administration manual so you will have a good reference book on hand during you instalation.
<p>
A number of sites may need to be true Primary Domain sites, and thus will need some special help on configuring <a href="nishelp.htm">NIS</a>.  Fortunately SCO does a good job with Global Access.
<p>
Once you have the three utilities above installed, then its time to install Global Access.  Global Access is installed just like any other custom application on SCO, by using the "custom" command.  Once the upgrade has been read from tape, you will be asked to run the "mkdev internet" command.  You will need the following information...
<p>
<ul>
<li>The IP address of the gateway (the machine your PPP links calls into)
<li>The name of the gateway machinee (teh full name thank you very much)
<li>The IP address of the Internet provider's nameserver
<li>The name of the Internet provider's nameserver machine
<li>Your machine's IP address
</ul>
<p>
Global Access will modify some key files for you in order to get the PPP link configured properly.  In order to adequalty test and maintain the PPP interface, we
recommmend you look at how Global Access modifies the following files:
<p>
<code>/usr/lib/uucp/Dialers<br>
/usr/lib/uucp/Systems<br>
/usr/lib/uucp/Devices<br>
/etc/rc2.d/S85tcp<br>
</code><p>
We also find what we believe is a major bug in the SCO implementation, the 
<code>named</code> nameserver startup script does not handle the file
<code>/etc/resolv.conf.d</code> properly.  Modify this script to do the following
if the administrator request startup of NIS...
<p>
<code>mv resolv.conf.d resolv.conf</code>
<p>
Also, in the "stop" section of the script, you will need to do the following:
<code>mv resolv.conf resolv.conf.d</code>
<p>
You might to look this script over.  There are a number of holes in the way
SCO handles the NIS startup...for instance, if the script fails, a later invokation will most likely clobber the resolv.conf and named.boot files.  Serious trouble here!
<p>
Another problem, is that the Global Access's script for "mkdev internet" (which is run after the installation has been completed), changes the permissions on <code>/etc/routed</code>, so that it won't run, wile at the same time adding a "static" route which points at the PPP host (your gateway to the Internet).  
<p>
We believe this (and perhaps the lack of a <code>gated</code> configuation prevents the machine with global access configured, to act as a gateway to teh 
internet for other machines on your local LAN.  Course, this might be a nice 
feature if you have machines you don't want on the net.  But if the converse is true, i.e. you  want to add a number of servers to the web, then you will need to take some special action.  At this point we should recommend a good text on networking...so we will!:
<p>
O'Reilly & Associates, Inc. has an excellent text whch can help you with setting up for connection to the Internet.  The title is <i><b>TCP/IP Network Administration</b>/i>.  The copy I have seen as a big 'ole crab drawing on the front.  (ISBN 0-937175-82-X).



<p>
<p>
<hr>
<address>onestep@onestep.com</address>

</DOC>
