<HTML>
<TITLE>OneStep Internet Services Provider Services - Do Your Own NT</TITLE>
<p><center>
	            <img src="1steplog.gif">
<p>
<p>
 		                  <a href="onestep.htm"><img src="puzzle.gif"></a>
<p>
<img src="../undrcons.gif" alt="Under Construction"><br>
This page is intended to always be under construction so please take a look around.  There is just no other way to bring you leading edge knowlege without constantly rewriting and rephrasing. <p>

</center><H1>OneStep Internet Services Provider Services - Do Your Own NT 
</h1>
<p>
Okay, good decision (if you look at the UNIX branch, we say the same thing...either choice is good).  Here is what you need to price before finalizing your decision.
<ul>
<b><li></b>486, 33Mhz minimum (don't buy a Pentium if you are using 14.400 baud and PPP...a 486 will stay ahead of the datacomm, no problem!), 
16MB RAM (more is better), 200MB disk space (more is better).  If you're installiing NT or SCO, you only really need a 640X480 VGA card, but higher res is more fun.  
Obviously you rmonitro should match your VGA card.
We recommend you go SCSI interface for Disks and CDROMs...it costs more but allows you more flexibility as you grow your server requirements (moving a SCSI disk to a new system is easier than any other).
<p>
You'll need a mouse and CDROM to load Microsoft NT.  Version 3.5 is a must.  If you find a good deal on NT version 3.1, consider it only costs about $100 to upgrade that to 3.5 (as of 6/7/95...I know I bought the upgrade).  At the same store,  I would have had to pay $395 for a "full" NT version 3.5 OS package.
<p>
<b><li></b>You should buy yourself a 16 bit or better NE2000 compatible network card.  We recommend this cuz the NE2000 compatibles easily transport across all OS and hardware environments in the Intel based server world.  The card will offer you great utility for years.
<p>
<b><li></b>For http software (that's the server software that makes web pages available over the Internet), you also have two choices...buy a commercial (low end first please) package, or download one of several public domain packages.  
If you pick the right commercial package, you can upgrade later to a "transaction" based commercial server that will allow for secure financial transactions (a must for really doing any realtime order fulfillment over the Internet).  
We are compiling a list of good NT server packages as we test...for now we can give you a thumbs up on "Purveyor".  We'll get a link or an address on here in the next week or so.
<p>
Okay, let's assume you got an eval copy of Purveyor.  What does that give you.  Like many Windows NT packages, a CDROM falls out when you pop open the packaging, and if you forgot to buy the CD, this is where that grimace hits you.  Same goes for the Windows 3.5 upgrade package.  Our bargain 3.5 software kept asking for "Disk #4" when trying to install from floppy...good thing we had the CD drive, cuz they packaged both media.

<p>
Now a word to our friends from UNIX land.  Windows NT experts should take note as well.  Much of the Internet is implemented in UNIX environments.  Certainly the networking is TCP/IP expert land at the least.  So when we start talking about Windows NT,
we are going to try to relate back to the UNIX and TCP/IP audience.  You Windows gurus will just have to ignore the UNIX and TCP/IP rhetoric as best as you can.<p>
The installation steps for Windows NT are as numerous as UNIX, but you feel better about it cuz its pretty Microsoft Windows...well at least after awhile.  Here is a summary of the steps we went through:
<ol>
<b><li></b>Initial load - Pop in CD, and the CD boot disk for Windows 3.1 (assuming you go the buy 3.1 and upgrade route).  Boot the machine.
<b><li><Our SCSI card wasn't in the list...NT has to know where the CDROM is, and ours is SCSI.  Required a quick search of the SCSI controller packaging to find a OS/2 and NT drivers disk.
<b><li></b>Slip in the SCSI driver disk and go through three, count 'em, three prompts to make sure this is really what you want to do (makes you wonder if you are about to crush the machine, huh.  We used to kid about a machine that would intone in a sepuchrial voice, "Please duck, ejecting sharp pointy disk thingy!"
<b><li></b>Now confirm your hard disk is to converted into a "NTFS" system disk.  You will not get very far if you don't do this...you need the added security of NTFS for WEB access.
<b><li></b>NT goes away and converts (may include formatting).
<b><li></b>Now you get to choose your directory for the OS. Go ahead and use C:\WINNT, it can't hurt.   
<b><li></b>And away you go...it now looks a lot like standard Windows installation.
<b><li></b>Eventually you are asked to reboot the system.  Things get interesting again.
<b><li></b>NT will now take the DOS formatted disk and add the NTFS structure on top.  This will take some time, and yes, another reboot.
<b><li><As you get closer to the more generic windows installation, you will find that you are building windows "group" with familar icons such as Control Panel and the like.
<b><li></b>You will make some networking decisions along the way, telling NT how to be a Windows for Workgroup smart computer.  You might try skipping this as NT 3.5 upgrade will force you to do it over again.  But...we recommend you deny that impulse and go through it.
<b><li></b>You will be asked to create a password for Administrator (for you former UNIX lovers, that is root's password we are messing with here).  Just for fun, we always create a second admin password by using the User Admin utility...you can simply selet Administrator and pull down on the edit menu for COPY,and wholla! you have a backup admin user...UNIX lovers might make this new user named root.
<b><li></b>Now that you have NT installed.  Its time to do the upgrade. 
</ol>
<p>
<h2>Adding Windows 3.5 Upgrade</h2>
<p>
Well now.  If you already have a machine with NT 3.1 on it, you should have skipped here first.  The NT 3.5 upgrade kit has a CDROM or 3 floppies.  As we mentioned earlier, ours had a problem asking for floppy number four.  So we had to abort our upgrade and go back to using the CDROM. Here are some of the more interesting steps we had to take to get NT 3.5 installed:
<p>
<ol>
<b><li></b>Select Custom installation, just to see what's going on if nothing else.  Oh by the way, we are going to go through the SCSI driver exercise again if you have a SCSI controller not recognized by NT.  Don't ask me why...I guess Microsoft want you to!
<b><li></b>As you wind up the OS installation, the services start to configure and this is where you get busy.
<b><li></b>Install everything. 
<b><li></b>USE TCP/IP options were you are given them.  In otherwords, the INTERNET is not a Windows for Workgroup domain...and we are not sure how you can get non-TCP/IP networks to talk to the INTERNET. 
<b><li></b>You will be pleased to note that if you had installed Word For Windows or Excel (or we presume other 32 bit apps for Windows), they will still be there after you upgrade to 3.5.
<b><li></b>For UNIX lovers, you'll find some standard TCP/IP ASCII files in \WINNT\SYSMTEM32\ETC (ain't that sweet?), like /etc/hosts (\etc\hosts), resolv.cfg (resolv.conf).  You will also see protocols.ini (NDIS style stack variables) and some samples.
<b><li></b>If you didn't understand the item above, don't worry you may not need to.
The installation will prompt you for IP addresses.  If you understand IP addresses, go see our <a href="ipprimer.htm">IP primer</a>.  In any case the Windows NT approach is to help you type in the four octets of the IP address, then you click on a add button.  This copies the octet from the box at the left (where you entered it) into a box on the right (this is good user interface?).  When you are done, don't click on okay.
<b><li></b>There are several other similar functions to go through.  You will need IP address for your domain name server (probably one on your access provider's side of the network), your gateway (if your using PPP this is the IP of the host you connect to), and the name of of your machine (your provider probably helped you pick one).
<b><li></b>We should note that WINS and LMHOSTS are terms from non-TCP/IP parts of the world, and we are not all that sure how to use them so we'll skip them for now, as they don't seem necessary to get the server up and running.
<b><li></b>Once you have selected and entered and "ok'ed a few times, your TCP/IP experience on NT will finish.  
<b><li></b>Guess what, you don't have to recreate any users or reinstall sofware.  Just thought we'd point that out again.  Major updates in the UNIX world sometime require a lot of file backups to preserve your administrative environment...not so on NT.
</ol>
<p>
Now that you have NT up, it's time to install your WEB Server software.  This is not too bad, until you start getting asked about access rights.  Most of the packages we've glanced at do this through the file manager, so if you are Windows illiterate it will be a shock.  Heck even if you use Windows everyday, its a shock.  We should say you need to be NT admin literate...user admin and access rights on NT use a whole new vocabulary and is not familiar to Windows or UNIX users alike.  The functionality appears to be there, just a little different viewpoint.
<p>
We used the Purveyor package as our final choice to spend time on a full install.  This was easy until it came time to figure out what the data directory was.  We knew it had to do with where the web pages went...but what did it really mean.  It became clear a little later when we got to setting up server access the directory.  The Purveyor (and possibly other NT based WEB servers) package automatically user level authentication, and quite easily.  In fact, you have to read the book a little to figure out how NOT to lock everybody out of your web pages.
<p>
UNIX lovers will fight this for a little bit, but when the light bulb goes off, we think they'll agree its really cool!  For instance, implementing an "internal only" web space within your existing web pages is trivial.  Just enter a wildcarded IP address for the appropriate individuals and away you go.  Doing this for a diverse group is a little harder, and you may still need some CGI routines to grab a password from an external membership, but that is the only complex part of this NT implementation.
<p>
We set up our data directory as c:\httpd\htdocs so that it would look like our SCO directory setup.  Presumably we can add our CGI-BIN directory later.  In order to do this, we had to add an access descriptor (in one box,  click on add to get it to appear in another box...NT strikes again).  We used a user of "*", and an IP of "*".  This allows anyone in.
<p>
Note:  Purveyor will not let you out of the initial configuration until you add at least some kind of access restriction, even if it is like ours...no restriction.  You just have to be EXPLICIT about alllowing everyone in.  Not much different than UNIX...the Purveyor package just doesn't have a set of defaults that are are like those you take for granted in the UNIX environment
.
<p>
<p>
<hr>
<address>onestep@onestep.com</address>

</DOC>
