<HTML>
<TITLE>OneStep Internet Services Provider Services - Write Your Own</TITLE>
<p><center>
	            <img src="1steplog.gif">
<p>
<p>
 		                  <a href="initial.htm"><img src="puzzle.gif"></a> 
</center>
 
<H1>OneStep Internet Services Provider Services - Write Your Own</h1>
<p>
 Designing and implementing your own home page is not as daunting task as you may think.  The majority of the work you will be doing is nothing more than what you or someone in your organization already knows how to do, organize and write clearly.  We provide the following documents online for those who wish to skip directly to the technical jargon and bypass this tutorial:
<p>
<ul>
<li><a href="../html/htmlprim.html">Short Tutorial</a>
<li><a href="../html/htmlqref.html">Quick Reference Guide</a>
<li>Complete <a href="../html/tags.html">HTML Specification</a> 
<li>Complete <a href="../html/htmldtd.html">HTML DTD</a>
<li>An <a href="../html/htmlalph.html">Alphabetical Summary</a>
<li>A <a href="gloss.htm">Brief Glossary</a>
</ul>
<p>
Home page's are nothing more than a document (or series of documents) that deliver your message to your intended audience.  Whether it be your current employees, your current customer base or a host of new potential customers on the Internet, most likely you already have messages and formats for how you deliver those messages. 
<p>
<h2>Graphics Conversion</h2>
 If your message is comprised of simply plain text, then you are already about 90% done.  If there is graphics involved however, you will need to convert those graphics into an electronically readable form...a form such as a <a href="htbitmap.htm">bitmap</a> or GIF file.  We can help you in making these "<a href="htbitmap.htm#weconvert">file conversions</a>".
<p>
Once you have the graphics converted, and your text written, then it is just a matter of marrying the two together into a consistent looking document suitable for your audience.
<p>
<p>
<pre>				   <img src="heirarch.gif">
</pre>
<h2>Creating the Heirarchy</h2>
<p>
A Home Page is more than just a single page of data displayed on the audience's computer screen.  It is actually a series of interlocked pages, held together in a loose heirachy by the first page the computer user sees.  The Home Page itself is the first page, and it is where you first get the attention of  your target user, allowing them to peruse your messages by clicking on links to the other pages.
<p>
But before you start writing home page text and symbols, you probably should take a some time to <a href="layout.htm">layout</a> the heirarchy of the pages that follow your home page.^M
<p>
<p>
<center>			   <img src="1xx.gif">
</center>
<H2>Creating the Home Page</h2>
<p>
Once you know how your are going to piece your web pages together, then it is time to actually begin creating your home page.  The first thing to be done is create a "document" using a standard plain text editor such as "vi", "ed", or others in the UNIX environment, or "Wordstar", "Word for Windows", "Write", "Notepad", or "Edit" in the DOS environment, or "MacWrite" or "Microsoft Word for Mac" in the Macintosh environment.  In any of the cases above, you output your text into an ASCII (plain text) file.  This file then is loaded into a special area where Internet users can "browse" around in it using Mosaic or other World Wide Web "browsers".
<p>
The text will need to have special symbols embedded along with your messages, symbols that tell our target user's Web Browsers how to pretty up the words in your document.
<p>
<a NAME="boldedtext"></a>For instance, the heading for this section, <b>Creating the Home Page</b> consists of nothing more than plain text with a couple of special symbols embedded to make "Creating the Home Page" bolded and a bit larger.  This is the bold command.  To bold text you would type:<p>
<pre>      <b><tt>&lt;b></tt></b>Creating the Home Page<b><tt>&lt;/b></tt></b></pre><p>
These symbols, and a few more like them, are all part of the special language used to create documents for your web server...a language called HTML (Hyperlink Text Markup Language).
<p>
We have a <a href="../html/htmlprim.html">Short Tutorial</a> available, a <a href="../html/htmlqref.html">quick reference guide</a>, as well as a document series that provides the complete <a href="../html/tags.html">Specification</a> for the "HTML" language. We also have a local copy of the <a href="../html/htmlalph.html">Alphabetical Summary</a> online as well.   And for the more technical folks interested in learning about HTML, we have the complete <a href="../html/htmldtd.html">HTML DTD</a> available locally as well.   Don't worry about all these documents however, the language really is as simple as our <a href="#boldedtext">bolded</a> text example shown above.
<p>
<h2>Downloading our Sample Home Page</h2>
<p>
</DOC>
