<HTML>
<TITLE>MILNET:  Military Information - Threats - Terrorism</TITLE>
<body bgcolor="#80e0f0">

<center>
<img align=middle src="milnetsm.gif">
<p>
<p>
<a href="milnet.htm"><img alt="Milnet Main" align=middle src="milico.gif"></a>
<a href="intell.htm"><img alt="Intell" align=middle src="intell.gif"></a>
<p>
<p>
<H1>The Threat of Terrorism</h1>
</center>
<img src="/milnet/rainbar3.gif">
<p>
<img src="/undrcon2.gif">  Under Construction: While not a new threat to the security of any of the world's countries, public exposure to this threat and large funding to combat this threat are only recently getting the attention they
deserve.  Consequently, we are behind in detailing much of this threat area.  
<p>
In the mid to late 1960s, terrorism was one of the top three threats to Israel in the MidEast, and one of the top ten throughout Europe.  Since that period,
terrorism has become a strategic level threat to every country in the world.
<p>
Strategic in that resources necessary to combat this worldwide threat must 
be planned and implemented at the highest level of a nation's government.
In addition,,those watching the progressive destructive ability of Terrorism
have remarked in private and now recently publicly that the threat of use of 
weapons of mass destruction is only an event waiting to happen. 
<p>
In any case, the threat consists of various components:
<p>
<ul>
<li><a href="/milnet/tweap.htm">Weapons used in Terrorism</a>
<li><a href="/milnet/tgroups.htm">Terrorist Groups</a>
<li><a href="/milnet/terrfile.htm">Terrorist Activities</a>
</ul>

<p>
In general however, the activities category is the most dynamic of the
components and bears the most scrutiny.
<p>
Early terrorist activities (we speak now of modern terrorism) became a plague
in the mid 1960s as part of the Arab-Jew conflict which began in the early
years of recorded time.  The modern version, for perhaps the first time in 
human history spread well beyond a limited sphere of influence.  The exception
is the spread of the British-Irish and Protestant-Catholic conflicts 
one associates with the "Irish Problem", which is perhaps the other most
significant "event producer".
<p>
This spread of terrorist activity beyond a small sphere of influence has 
produced the fear and response that terrorism has never had in the past. Most
key however, is that this terrorism development requires worldwide planning
<b>AND</b> worldwide assets to combat.  Thus the increased level of threat
has produced an increased threat response.
<p>
Hardly a country is left where there is not an <a href="/milnet/elite.htm">elite</a> crew
of special forces are assigned (dedicated duties typically) to go where the
terrorist can be found, rescue hostages, and eliminate as necessary.
<p>
Terrorist Activities starting in the 1980s took on a new significance as 
Terrorists were able to muster the resources to not only attack innocent 
civilians, but attack military forces at rest.  Sad examples for the American
soldier were the truck bombs used at the Marine Barracks in Lebanon, and 
the attack on the <a href="/milnet/dhahran.htm">Khobar Towers</a> outside of Dhahran, Saudi Arabia.
<p>
It is a sad state of affairs when a sophisticated military force such as
that of the U.S. cannot protect itself from a few individuals and a truck
bomb.  However, rather than place blame on our leaders, it is clear that the
situations our troops are placed in are as much at fault as any human error.
<p>
Today, soldiers worldwide are exchanged in an effort to foster better
combined force operations, as well as based together in order to facilitate
more efficient-less costly basing arrangements.  However, any good military
manager will tell you that this breaks a major military tenet, and thus 
provides for opportunities for an increased number of human errors which
thus provide additional opportunities for terrorist attacks on military
forces.
<p>
See the <a href="/milnet/terror.htm">Terrorism</a> section of MILNET for definitions of terrorism and other
related information.
<p>

<center>
<img src="/milnet/rainbar3.gif">
</center>
<p>
For more information on the MILNET project, write email to: 
<a href="mailto:milnet@onestep.com"><i>milnet@onestep.com</i></a>
<p>
