<title>MILNET - U.S. Military Police Actions</title>
<center>
<h1>MILNET:  U.S. Military Police Actions</h1>
<hr>
</center>
<p>
Following World War II, the United States, as a member of the United Nations,
has participated in a number of "police actions", military operations, that 
either alone or in conjunction with a coalition of United Nations members, have
been initiated to help police choatic or cruel conditions in nations 
throughout the world.  Many of these operations have been to help police and
protect citizens during times of upheaval (Somalia) or to repulse or eject invaders into smaller nations (Kuwait during the Gulf War).  In most modern cases, U.S.
troops have acted as part of a broad spectrum of U.N. forces, sometimes as 
the leaders or as willing followers.  There are, of course, a number of <a href="/milnet/conflict.htm">conflicts</a> the U.S. has participated in.  
<p>
Due to the force projection capabilities of the U.S. Navy, the U.S. has been called on during a number of crisis to provide a show of force, and in some cases
actually take action from Naval Bombardment positions (Beirut).  And in some 
cases retaliation from warring factions has resulted in many U.S. servicemen's 
death.  And of course actions on the ground, Naval bombardment, or from the 
air (Air Force or Navy) have resulted in U.S. losses.  Thus there is a price 
we as a nation pay to be part of the global police force, just as every police
department knows in a major metropolitan city.
<p>
Below is a summary of some of the important police actions the U.S. has taken 
part in since since World War II:
<p>
<ul>
<li><a href="/milnet/nokorea.htm">Korea</a>:  Mission to repel 
a North Korean invasion into South Korea resulting in a protracted war 
costing a large number of U.S. lives (the leader of an otherwise token
U.N. force).  The U.S. used aircraft carriers and Naval Aviation from 
those carriers for the first time, to mount sorties against North Korean
forces, solidifing the techniques used later in the Vietnam War.
<li>Vietnam:  While perhaps intended as a police action, the Vietnam War became
a major political effort which stemmed from a fairly minor incident in the 
Gulf of Tonkin in Vietnam.  U.S. forces up to that point were mostly clandestine
and "consultants".  However, after this event, the U.S. went in "with both feet"
and the war escalated quickly to something well beyond the U.N. intensions.
<li>Middle East - Various attempts to help U.N. forces stem the fall of 
middle eastern nations to chaos, including the bombardment of Beirut to 
force compliance of Syrian forces to exit Lebanon.  The result of this operation
was a terrorist bombing (technically a state of war existed in the nation
however, the forces thought to have caused the bombing had no country to 
retaliate against, therefore are defined as terrorists) of the U.S. Marine 
Barracks outside of Beirut, killing hundreds of U.S. soldiers.
<li>Africa - A number of small nations have gone through famine and tribal
disintegration, with the resulting chaos compelling U.N. forces to intervene.
The U.S. has been part of these actions.  The most visible was 
<a href="/milnet/reshope.htm">Operation Restore Hope in Somalia</a>.
Recently there has been a similar opportunity to help Rawandian refugees who 
have fled to <a href="/milnet/zaire.htm">Zaire</a>, however the situation has been in such flux (the refugees
deciding en masse to return with no notice) that no forces have officially been
sent. 
<li> <a href="/milnet/gulfwar.htm">Kuwait</a>:  Resulting in the Gulf War, ejecting 
Iraqi forces from this small country.  Probably one of the shortest actual fighting war in the history books.
<li>Haiti:  To prevent the overthrow of the duly elected government, the U.S.
threatened to invade <a href="/milnet/haitix.htm">Haiti</a>, and in fact were
offshore poised to invade before the malcreants relented.
<li><a href="/milnet/bosnia.htm">Bosnia</a>:  U.N. forces (led by the U.S) 
moved in to relieve Sarejevo, a city
surrounded by one of the warring factions.  The issues here, as usual, are 
complex, and while clearly on their way to being resolved, there is still 
sporadic fighting and we are still learning of atrocities committed by both
warring factions.
</ul>
<p>
There are of course many other U.N. missions that U.S. troops have been 
part of, the list is rather long.  A fun way to look at these would be to 
scan the U.N. Service decorations of the Canadians, posted on the 
<a href="http://www.lfc.dnd.ca/english/equip/unidec/decor/dec02.htm">
Land Forces Command</a> Home Page (Official Candian Army Page)
; the link is to their decorations pages.
<p>
