<center>
<img align=middle src="milnetsm.gif" alt="Milnet">
<p>
<p>
<a href="milnet.htm"><img alt="Milnet Main" align=middle src="milico.gif"></a>
<a href="intell.htm"><img alt="Intell" align=middle src="intell.gif"></a>
</center>
<p>
<p>
<H1>MILNET:  U.S. Intelligence Agencies - The FBI</h1>
<p>
The FBI conducts counter-intelligence activities in the U.S. (among its other, more visible duties).  The FBI is also concerned with anti-terrorism as a subset of counter-intelligence.  Neither organizations within the FBI have public visibility and data on their structures is almost non existent.  The FBIs counter-intelligence performance has been likened in the recent past to "...spys fall all over themselves to get caught and occassionally the FBI is successful in their capture." 
<p>
<pre>
			   <a href="fbifail.htm"><img src="fbifail.gif"></a></pre>
<p>
<p>
The structure of the FBI is based roughly on their assigned tasks (as defined in the National Security Act of 1947):
<p>
<ul>
<li>Counter-Intelligence - Investigation,  Surveillance, Tracking, Capturing, and otherwise Disabling espionage in the U.S.
<li>Persuing Federal Offenders - Investigation, Surveillance, Tracking, and Capture of those criminals breaking federal criminal statutes.
<li>Assisting local authorities in crimes suspected of crossing state boundaries.
<li>Anti-Terrorism (classed as a federal crime)
</ul>

</DOC>
