<title>MILNET Military Information:  Japan ASDF</title>
<p>
<center>
<img align=middle src="milnetsm.gif">
<p>
<a href="milnet.htm"><img alt="Milnet Main" align=middle src="milico.gif"></a>
<a href="intell.htm"><img alt="Intell" align=middle src="intell.gif"></a>
<p>
<h1>Japan Air Self Defense Forces (ASDF)</h1>
</center>
<hr>

The Air Self Defense Force protects Japans air space as well as the sea lanes.  This force also conducts reconaissance with a 14 aircraft squadron of RF-4EJ reconaissance jets and fields nine squadrons of F-15J Eagle air superiority fighters and F-4EJ Phantom IIs all armed with AIM-7 Sparrow radar homing missiles and AIM-9 Sidewinder infrared seeking missiles.  The Air Self Defense Force has more than 400 aircraft and better than 45,000 men and women (Air Force Magazine, November 1989, pg. 44).
<p>
The Japanese Air Self Defense Force intercepts several hundred intrusions by Soviet aircraft every year.  Also, a fleet of Japanese built F-1 single seat supersonic attack fighters would support ground forces in the interdiciton mission.  These are armed with Japanese Type-89 air to ground missiles, 750 pound bombs, and four AIM-9 Sidewinders.
<p>
Japan has also been working on building the SX-3, a design based on an advanced version of the F-16.
<p>
ASDF has fields a fleet of eight E-2C Hawkeyes, with an additional two to come online in 1991 and a total of 42 E-2C on order.

<p>
<hr>
Last Updated: 12/1/87
