<title>MILNET:  Terrorism - March News Stories</title>
<center>
<img src="milnetsm.gif" align=middle, alt="Milnet">
<p>
<p>
<a href="milnet.htm"><img src="milico.gif" align=middle alt="Milnet Main"></a>
<a href="terror.htm"><img src="terror.gif" align=middle alt="Terrorism"></a>
<p>
<p></center>
<H1>March 1993</H1>
The following news stories are from the first week in March.  Click on  more  to see more March 
TerrFile.<P>
<P>
<B>UPDATE: U.S. EMBASSY IN BELGRADE IS TARGET OF "MINOR" GRENADE 
ATTACK</B>  BELGRADE (MARCH 3) UPI - Gunmen threw what police said was a hand 
grenade near the main entrance of the U.S. Embassy and fired several shots at the facility late 
Wednesday, but no injuries were reported in the driveby attack.<P>
	Belgrade police called the blast outside the embassy "a minor explosion" and reported a 
plaque that read "American Embassy" was struck by gunfire as the assailants drove past.<P>
	The explosion, which occurred several yards outside the main entrance of the embassy, 
caused some plaster chips to fall from an exterior wall around the embassy courtyard and shook 
some windows on the embassy building.<P>
 	Meanwhile, U.S. officials said only that the blast was caused by a small incendiary device 
that exploded near the U.S. Embassy in Belgrade but reported no injuries and said the 
"firecracker-like noise" caused no damage to the complex.<P>
 	A State Department spokesman, Martin Judge, said in Washington that the device 
apparently was set off late Wednesday evening when U.S. workers were not present.<P>
 	"There was a loud firecracker-like noise outside the embassy at 11 p.m. their time," he 
said.<P>
	Judge said no report was immediately available about the incident but was able to confirm 
that no U.S. officials were harmed and that the embassy was undamaged.<P>
 	He said an embassy official was "on the way there" to investigate the situation. "We expect 
further reports but not before tomorrow morning," he added.<P>
Transmitted:  93-03-03 20:04:00 EST<P>
<P>
<a name="koresh">
<B>UPDATE: FBI SEEKS PEACEFUL END TO STANDOFF DESPITE KORESH'S REFUSAL 
TO GIVE UP</B>   WACO, TX (MARCH 3) UPI - Cult leader David<P>
 Koresh told negotiators he reneged on his promise to peacefully end his bloody four-day 
standoff with federal officers because he received a message from God telling him to wait, the 
FBI said Wednesday.<P>
 	FBI Special Agent in Charge Jeff Jamar revealed Koresh's explanation during a news 
conference, but he vowed federal authorities would continue to seek a peaceful end to the siege 
that cost the lives of four federal agents and an unknown number of Koresh's followers.<P>
  	Jamar said negotiators contacted Koresh two hours after his 58- minute religious message 
was broadcast nationally Tuesday. The Branch Davidian leader had promised to surrender with 
his followers immediately after the sermon-like statement ended.<P>
 	"Subsequent contacts with Koresh indicated that he had received a message from God 
instructing him to wait," he said. "The negotiation team undertook efforts to convince Koresh to 
fulfill his promise and surrender immediately. Koresh refused to honor his promise and has 
indicated he will keep his promise when he receives further instruction from God."<P>
 	Jamar also said Koresh claims there were 110 people still inside the compound, more than 
officials had originally estimated. Jamar said Koresh gave a breakdown of 20 children, 47 
women and 43 men still inside the 77-acre compound 10 miles east of Waco.<P>
 	Since the siege began, Jamar said 18 children and two elderly women have been 
released.<P>
 	Jamar said interviews with those who had been released and with officers who took part in 
Sunday's gunbattle left the impression that Koresh and two others were wounded. He said the 
interviews "indicated there are some bodies in the compound, the precise number we don't 
know. "<P>
 	Asked why the agents assaulted the compound if they knew it was heavily armed, Hartman 
said "months and months" of preparation had gone into the investigation and they were acting 
because of the threat the arsenal of firearms posed to public safety. 	<P>
	"The element of surprise was essential for us to get in," Hartman said. "There were over 75 
women and children. We have a fire discipline. We are law enforcement officers who can't fire 
without having a target. So when we went in and they opened fire,  we were halfway into the 
place when they opened fire."<P>
  	Child welfare officials have reported no signs of physical abuse in the children released. 
There have been charges by former cult members that Koresh physically and sexually abused 
children, but he has denied the accusations.<P>
 	The siege began at 9:30 a.m. Sunday when 150 to 200 ATF agents tried to execute a search 
warrant to look for illegal firearms and explosives at the compound - located in open central 
Texas farmland.<P>
 	Four ATF agents were killed and 15 wounded in the initial assault. Koresh claims a 2-year-
old child died, but ATF has been unable to confirm it. A cult member was killed, another 
wounded and a third arrested late Sunday in a separate firefight, the ATF said.<P>
  	An ATF spokeswoman has admitted that the ATF agents were "outgunned" by the so-called 
Branch Davidians, who had an arsenal of firearms including a 50-caliber heavy machinegun. 
Criticism of ATF planning is increasing.<P>
  	In an interview Wednesday with KRLD, retired Col. Charles Beckwith, former commander of 
the Army's Delta Force, called the ATF assault badly planned and a "disaster" for the federal 
agency.<P>
 	"The ATF says they were outgunned," he said. "That, to me, is an indicator that there was 
actually no intelligence collected from inside to know precisely what the capabilities of this 
organization were, and they just went charging in there with their jackets on saying ATF and 
everybody was suppose to lay down and nobody did and as a result it was a disaster."<P>
 	Hundreds of FBI and ATF agents, backed up by seven Bradley infantry fighting vehicles and 
armed personnel carriers, surround the Branch Davidian compound ruled by Koresh, a 33-year-
old former member of the Seventh-day Adventist Church who claims to be Christ.<P>
 	The elderly women who left the compound early Tuesday were charged with conspiracy to 
murder federal agents. Another cult member arrested Sunday is also charged with the attempted 
murder of a federal agent.<P>
Transmitted:  93-03-03 15:29:00 EST<P>
<P>
 <B>FOUR KILLED IN SOUTHERN PHILIPPINE BOAT EXPLOSION ZAMBOANGA,</B> 
PHILIPPINES (MARCH 3) UPI - Four people, including two Muslim government officials, were 
killed when an explosion ripped their boat apart in southern Philippine waters, the military and 
relatives said Wednesday.<P>
  	Relatives said the four died of their wounds at a hospital one day after a blast of 
undetermined origin rocked their speedboat Tuesday off Tawi-tawi province, 700 miles south of 
Manila.<P>
  	Tawi-tawi Gov. Gerry Matba, who was also aboard the vessel at the time of the explosion, 
was escaped without injury.<P>
 	Authorities identified the fatalities as regional assemblyman Kadir Ibrahim, provincial board 
member Hashim Diamalul and their two security escorts.<P>
 	A report to military headquarters in Zamboanga, 190 miles northeast of Tawi-tawi, said the 
victims were en route from Languyan town to another village when the blast occurred.<P>
 	Ibrahim was running for a second term as a legislator in the Muslim autonomous region 
during elections scheduled later this month. The other people in the boat were his 
supporters.<P>
 	Military officials said the cause of the blast could not be determined.<P>
  	One of the victims relatives told United Press International the engine of the boat "backfired," 
triggering the blast. But a second relative said he was not ruling out the possibility a time bomb 
had been placed on the vessel before it sailed.<P>
 	The autonomous region comprises four Muslim-dominated provinces in the main southern 
island of Mindanao. It was formed in 1989 as an alternative to demands for a separate Muslim 
state in the largely Roman Catholic country.<P>
  	Muslim rebels have fought a bloody war for independence in Mindanao since the 1970s, but 
the rebellion has largely been crushed.<P>
  	President Fidel Ramos last year offered to talk peace with the Muslim separatists and the 
country's two other main insurgent groups - communist guerrillas and right-wing army rebels.
	<P>
Transmitted:  93-03-03 05:52:00 EST<P>
<P>
 <B>BOMBS EXPLODE IN CENTRAL MADRID DAMAGING OFFICES; NO INJURIES 
REPORTED</B>, MADRID, SPAIN (MARCH 3) UPI - Three bombs exploded in central Madrid 
Wednesday, damaging buildings but causing no injuries in attacks police attributed to the First of 
October Revolutionary Anti-Fascist Group (GRAPO).<P>
  	"What we know is that a voice claiming to speak on behalf of GRAPO telephoned and said 
these attacks were going to happen," said the government delegate in Madrid, Miguel 
Solans.<P>
 	"That is the only information we have. But from the form of the attacks you can assume that 
it was them. This shows the signs of a GRAPO operation."<P>
  	The three bombs exploded within half an hour in the headquarters buildings of the Spanish 
Confederation of Business Organizations (CEOE), the Provincial Work Delegation of Madrid and 
the country's Steel Confederation.<P>
  	All were placed in the building's toilets and warning phone calls were received at each place 
from someone claiming to represent GRAPO.<P>
  	The attacks were similar to two carried out at the Ministry of Works and National Industry 
Institute in April 1992. Two policemen were injured in those attacks. Both were claimed by 
GRAPO.<P>
  	The organization - which carried out its first attack with the murder of four police officers on 
Oct 1, 1975 - has previously also planted bombs in the Stock Exchange, the Finance Ministry 
and the Constitutional Court.<P>
Transmitted:  93-03-03 10:06:00 EST<P>
<P>
 <B>ALGERIA - EXPLOSION DAMAGES CHIEF TELEPHONE EXCHANGE</B> (MAR. 3) 
MIDDLE EAST INTELLIGENCE REPORT - The security services in Chief Province report that 
the telephone exchange in the center of the town of Chlef was damaged on Friday (26 February) 
when a powerful home- made bomb exploded. The explosion wrecked about 4,000 telephone 
lines and three distribution points.<P>
From Radio Algiers Network in Arabic<P>
Date 01 March 1993<P>
Transmitted:  93-03-03 21:32:00 EST<P>
<P><B>
</B><B>ANGOLAN ARMY SAYS UNITA STEPPING UP ATTACKS ON CITY OF 
HUAMBO</B> LUANDA (MARCH 3) DPA - Fighting intensified Wednesday in Huambo, the 
second largest Angolan city, an Angolan army source said.<P>
  	Quoted by Angolan state television, the source in the armed force general staff said UNITA 
forces shelled the city throughout the night and in the morning. The source said government 
forces killed a number of UNITA troops and captured one.<P>
  	UNITA Tuesday set new conditions for negotiations with the MPLA government after failing 
to attend a second round of peace talks at the weekend in the Ethiopian capital Addis 
Ababa.<P>
  	A leading UNITA member, Jorge Justino, in an interview with Portuguese radio demanded 
that United Nations special envoy for Angola Margaret Anstee and the Portuguese Ambassador 
to Luanda, Antonio Moreiro, be relieved of their posts.<P>
  	UNITA also proposed that a next round of peace talks be held in a country in southern Africa 
which allowed easier travel.<P>
  	UNITA "Voice of the Resistance of the Black Cockerel radio said Wednesday government 
forces bombed the town of Caluquembe in the southern province of Huila, causing heavy 
civilian casualties.<P>
 	It said the air force bombed the town "intensively" in the afternoon using 250-kilo and 500-
kilo bombs. It said the damage to the town, southwest of Huambo, was "incalculable".<P>
Transmitted:  93-03-03 17:18:00 EST<P>
<P>
<B>PHILIPPINES - POLICE FIND MORE BOMBS IN ZAMBOANGA</B> (MAR. 3) PAC RIM 
INTELLIGENCE REPORT - Police authorities have found 18 more bombs in various locations in 
Zamboanga City. Security has been tightened, especially after receiving unconfirmed reports 
that some Muslim bandits from Sabah have arrived in several towns in the province.<P>
From DWIZ in Tagalog<P>
Date 01 March 1993<P>
Transmitted:  93-03-03 19:54:00 EST<P>
<P>
<B> GUNMEN KILL HIGH-RANKING EGYPTIAN POLICE OFFICER, SHOOT SON</B>, 
CAIRO (MARCH 3) UPI - Gunmen shot and killed a high-ranking member of Egypt's state 
security force and seriously injured his son late Wednesday in what police believe was a 
planned attack by Muslim militants.<P>
 	Lt. Col. Mohamed Mahran of the state security force was killed and his son seriously injured 
while driving in a private vehicle in El Daweer in the Assiut state, police said.<P>
 	Police said they believed the fatal shooting was planned and suspect Muslim militants. The 
attack occurred in an area where at least 90 people have been killed since last March in similar 
incidents.<P>
 	Muslim militants in Assiut are waging a campaign of violence in an attempt to topple the 
moderate secular government, and replace it with an Iranian-style theocracy. Militants have also 
launched attacks against tourists to further cripple the government.<P>
  	The latest incident occurred last Friday when a popular cafe in central Cairo was bombed, 
killing two tourists and an Egyptian.<P>
Transmitted:  93-03-03 22:22:00 EST<P>
<P>
<B> KNIGHT-RIDDER FINANCIAL NEWS--Tokyo, Thursday, Mar 4</B><P><B>
</B> <B>UN DEMANDS BOSNIAN SERBS TO HALT ATTACKS</B>--The UN Security 
Council Wednesday demanded that Bosnian Serbs halt their attacks in eastern  Bosnia and 
called for the deployment of UN monitors or troops to protect civilians. It was one of the council's 
strongest statements on the Balkan civil wars. But the 15-nation council was vague on whether it 
would dispatch UN forces.<P>
<P>
  <B>UN CHIEF WANTS MAY 1 FOR SOMALIA TRANSFER</B>--UN Secretary General 
Boutros Boutros-Ghali Wednesday recommended May 1 as the date for formally transferring US 
command of international forces in Somalia to the UN. He said that the new UN force in Somalia 
will consist of 28,000 troops, as well as 2,800 civilian workers.<P>
<P>
<B>S. KOREA PRESIDENT FIRES MAYOR OF SEOUL</B>--South Korean President Kim 
Young-Sam today fired Seoul City Mayor Kim Sang-Chul, only 6 days after his appointment, the 
presidential spokesman announced. The dismissal came after local newspapers reported that 
the mayor had illegally built a house in the so-called "Greenbelt Zone" in Seoul where 
construction is banned.<P>
<P>
<B>"GROUND ZERO" FOUND IN NEW YORK BOMBING</B>--Police investigators have 
located "ground zero" of the bomb that ripped through the base of the World Trade Center--a 
ramp of a parking garage directly beneath the Vista Hotel. The hotel is at the foot of the south 
tower.<P>
A police official said "in excess of several hundred pounds" of explosives were involved in the 
blast that killed five people.<P>
<P>
<B>G7 NATIONS TO DONATE FUNDS TO CONSERVE BRAZIL FOREST</B>--The Group of 
Seven industrialized nations will donate 270 million US dlrs toward Brazil's environment program 
to conserve the Amazon rain forest, the Brazil's environment minister said Wednesday. The 
continuing, large-scale depletion of Amazon rain forests is believed to present a serious threat to 
the global environment.<P>
<P>
   <B>STANDOFF CONTINUES FOR 4TH DAY IN TEXAS</B>--The siege between US agents 
and a heavily armed religious cult continued for a fourth day in Waco, Texas. While negotiations 
persisted on Wednesday, officials said the group's leader might have more than 100 followers 
and   "massive weapons cache" inside his fortified compound. As many as 14  people may have 
died in a shootout on Sunday.  End<P>
