<HTML>
<title>MILNET:  Explosive</title>
<center>
<img align=middle src="milnetsm.gif" alt="Milnet">
<p>
<p>
<a href="milnet.htm"><img alt="Milnet Main" align=middle src="milico.gif"></a>
<a href="intell.htm"><img alt="Intell" align=middle src="intell.gif"></a>
</center>
<p>
<p>
<H1>MILNET:  Explosives</h1>
<p>
This is not a course on how to build explosives, rather an examination of the
types of explosives available to military or terrorists...or actually,
available to just about anyone.
<p>
<h2>Explosive Classes</h2>
<p>
Ignoring Nuclear Weapons (now that's an explosive" quoteth the demolitions instructor at a police training session), there are four classes of explosives:
<dl><dl>
<dl><dl>
<ul>
<li>Home Equipped
<li>Factory Equipped
<li>Laboratory Equipped
<li>Military Equipped
</ul>
</dl></dl>
</dl></dl>
<p>
Now for any demolitions types out there, this probably looks like a strange 
way to classify explosives, but read on, it will become clear.  Remember this is
a briefing for the layman. And again, this briefing will 
refrain from giving much detail, and with respect to the younger folks out
there, DON'T EVEN THINK ABOUT THIS STUFF!  Right, like that's gonna stop 'em.
<p>
Before we carry on about these classes of explosives, lets talk about the level of explosive power
these  classes describe.  <p>
A <b>Home Equipped</b> class explosive (no not HE dunderhead), is
like gasoline.  Take a can of lawnmower gas, stick it in the trunk of a car and
light a very long cloth fuse.  When the flame starts to get close to the 
gas can, the fumes from the gasoline ignite, rupture the can from overpressure, spread more gasoline around in a fine mist, which in turn gets ignited, and so on.  A simple chemical chain reaction.  The combustion process, if unconfined, makes 
a nice ball of flame that expands til the outer fireball begins to cool, in which case the flame starts to smoke a bit, and thus you have a black smokey 
covering around a bright orange fireball.  Contained, the expansion of this 
fireball will rip a car to shreds, as well as knock walls out of a room if the
doors and windows are closed.  It will send glass flying at 60-70 MPH as it races away from the center of the explosion, being propelled by the rapid 
fireball expansion.  The heat would be felt by anyone 50 feet away, but then 
unless a person at 50 feet were extremly lucky, the shrapnel and debris would 
reach them much about the same time...the heat would probably not be an issue.
Anyone within 25 feet will be knocked down and probably suffer internal bleeding
and loss of lung tissue due to inhalation of the fireball.  Exterior surface 
burns would probably be near fatal, and the shock would certainly be terminal.
<p>
A <b>Factory Equipped</b> class explosive will have similar effects but at up to 3 times the range.  This class of explosion will most likely leave a mark on concrete (not
just a smudge, but heat distortion, pressure cracking, etc.).  This would be in
the class of a pipe bomb.  If shrapnel were added to the weapon, the shrapnel would speed ahead of the shockwave and pierce the siding of a house, building or
automobile at up to 100 feet.  Anyone standing in the open will get knocked down at that range, and survive if shrapnel didn't get them before they hit the 
ground.  At between 50 and 75 feet, the shockwave will compress the chest 
cavity and abdomen enough to cause internal bleeding, unconciousness, and 
probably the victim will go into terminal shock.  Within 50 feet, the effects 
are almost always deadly.
<p>
<b>Laboratory Equipped</b> class weapons are deadly if you are unprotected and
within 200 - 300 feet.  The explosive content in this class of weapon will 
leave a 20 - 30 foot crater.  Anything in that radius will be reduced to fragments, with large fragments being tossed away, not coincidentally to about
200 to 300 feet from the blast.  The reason this is the lethal radius of this 
type of explosive is that anything and everything inside the 100 foot readius will be ejected outward at the nearly the speed of sound.  Shrapnel will 
probably slow down quickly due to its non-aerodynamic properties, but within 
that 300 foot radius, still pierce just about anything it encounters, and 
treat human flesh as transparent.
<p>
<b>Military Equipped</b> class weapons carry the impact radius of a 500 lb bomb 
or larger.  This doesn't mean it has to be a 500 lb bomb, just have the explosive
power of such a weapon.  500 lbs of TNT will generate a fireball of several 
thousand degrees from impact to 200 feet almost instantaneously.  A 1000lb 
TNT blast will do the same at about 300 feet, and so on.  A trainful of 500 and 1000 lb bombs were in railroad cars on their way through Roseville, California 
in the 1975 to 1976 timeframe, when they caught fire.  At 20 to 30 miles
away, people heard and felt, distinctly, each and every explosion of each 
weapon.  Sounded much like sonic booms, one, right, after, another.  Chilling
actually.  Needless to say the people at the front of the long train ran like hell,
and still were pretty well banged up.  Homes a mile way suffered structural 
damage, and windows were broken up to 2 miles away.  SEMTEC won't do that, it
will just turn an automobile into fine, deadly shrapnel, or in "large amounts" will do about as much
damage as the Oklahoma City Bomb, while being able to be carried in a 
heavy but normal looking briefcase.
<p>
A 1 to 2lb brick of SEMTEC is kind of like a 500 lb bomb, perhaps not as much 
overall force, but it ignites and expands the fireball and shockwave at such 
a fierce rate, that it does very similar damage.  A brick as described could 
easily take out a support on a bridge.  Two or three such bricks and a terrorist
could topple a building, a bridge, an airport tower.  Good thing this stuff is
not all that easy to come by.  Unfortunately, there are military powers out 
there who have been selling this stuff to terrorists...we know cuz you can 
trace where the stuff is manufactured.   Eastern bloc countries have been
responsible for so much damage from their supply of this type of explosive, well
it is, simply put, criminal.  Oh, it could be supposed that the Western countries have 
"lost" a few hundred pounds over time as well.  It is not necessary to know where it has
dissappeared from, don't want to give anyone any ideas.  But again, it is 
difficult to find and VERY expensive.  You don't want any, or
want to know anyone who wants or has any.
Nor do you want to be around anyone who has any.  Plastique, C-4 for instance,
is not that dangerous to hold or carry, but its probably not a good idea to
 toss it out the window.
<p>
Now for a brief discussion on what these weapons are comprised of...no gory detail, just
 an idea of what's required, so you understand the dilemna low enforcement and goverment
agencies face when combatting people who build bombs. 
<p>
<h3>Home Equipped</h3>
<p>
Home Equipped explosives are those found around the house.  Taking certain
chemicals around the house, you can build yourself quite a nasty explosive.
If you are a farmer, you can probably buy enough fertilizer without raising
any eyebrows, to build a mean weapon (think Oklahoma City here).
<p>
As kids we used to make quite noisy and substantially deadly little toys out of
matches.  So devising a deadly weapon at home is even quite easy for 11 year 
olds.  Kinda scary huh.  Take a "toy" bomb of this type, and add something
pointy or lots of little somethings pointy, and you have a homemade grenade.
<P.
Another obvious example are bombs based upon normal "household" items such as
a can of gasoline.  Mix up a "cocktail" and you are armed.  There are lots
of ideas floating around, to go into them is pointless and again dangerous to
our younger visitors.   
<p>
Enough on that.  The point is that one does not have to gather huge funding to build
nasty killer weapons, nor a warehouse in the boonies to beginning manufacturing
such items.
<p>
<h3>A word about Fertilizer Bombs</h3>
<p>
Take two standard metal garbage cans, fill with fertilizer and some other 
easily obtainable stuff (you think it appropriate to go into detail...Nuts to
that!), and you now have a pretty big bang.  Fill the bed of a pickup with 
such cans and oh my, that's a major big deal.  It's not like you can walk into 
the local McDonalds with one of these.  But a crazy could...well never mind.  
Suffice to say, if someone wants to make a big bang and take out lots of people
in the process, all they have to do is buy fertilirzer, steal a car or pickup
truck, do a little mixing and "whoa-boy" its a hot time tonight!
<p>
Just about anyone who has lived on a big farm and half the people living near them can tell you how to 
do it.  Is that scary?  It should be.  Is this suddenly a new thing?  Nope.
Until Oklahoma City, the rest of us just didn't know just how deadly this 
kind of trash can bomb could be.
<P>
<h3>Factory Equipped</h3>
<p>
This class is those types of explosives that, by their nature, require some 
level of machining, drying, or mixing required to make the explosives at all.
Whether it is stable or too dangerous to handle at that point is really not
important to the manufacturer, we are still talking about low cost.  I exclude
such chemical reaction based weapons such as nitroglyceride based compounds,
however, cuz the more would be bombers that try to fry up nitro on their 
little hot plates, the less would be bombers we will have to worry about.
Examples of this class might be salt peter and sulfur smoke bombs, or other 
more flamei and gas producing mixtures.  
<p>
We say "Factory Equipped" because this kind of explosive, while probably not as dangerous as the next class, still require a repeatable process to be followed in order to repeatedly build significantly volatile explosives with dependablly accurate yields.  
<p>
In other words, you can make em at home, but to get the 
controllability and stablity, you would probably want to have a through and
stable process running in factory like conditions.  
<p>
Don't misunderstand, people can build such factories 
at home, so this doesn't preclude doing this in a spare bedroom or garage. 
<p>
One other point.  A good machinist can probably build a device that would 
mist liquid, then ignite it.  This is called a volatile weapon and multiples
the explosive force up to 10 times that of a liquid propellant in normal
evaporative or pressure separated explosion.  Air-Fuel mixtures require 
some precise timings to get those kind of multipliers, though, so unless
somebody has a laboratory to experiment with, they are probably gonna blow
themselves to hell and gone before they find the right setup for a 10 times
multiplier.
<p>
<h3>Laboratory Equipped</h3>
The next class is Laboratory Equipped.  This is the real stuff.  TNT is based
upon nitroglycerin or other such highly unstable and volatile chemical 
reaction by products.  By their nature, these kinds of explosives while possibly
built in modest surroundings, still require temperature control (cooling and 
heating at just right time or else an early "boom"), controlled mixing, and or
precise quanitities and measurements.  Thus a chemical laboratory is needed.
<p>
Again, a household bomb builder can find the necessary ingredients, but it
will take some real expertise to get it all to go together right while at the
same time not making a crater out of the wacko and his house. 
<p>
<h3>Military Equipped</h3>
For this class, you don't only need laboratory conditions, but access to 
chemical compounds that are known to be used primarily for explosives work.  Trying to buy the
ingredients for plastique, for example, is extremely difficult in most countries.  Not to say
it is impossible.  However, most users of plastique have purchased it either
directly from a military connection (stolen or "sanctioned" theft), or has 
themselves access to the chemicals in question (i.e. a commercial explosives
house might have access if they have military contracts).  
<p>
SEMTEC is a good
example.  In nearly all the SEMTEC bombs exploded in terrorist attacks, the
SEMTEC came from an Eastern Bloc country who either sold it at a huge discount, 
gave it away to their "partners", or after the wall came down, sold it just to
make a few bucks to get by.  SEMTEC is impossible to make without the 
access governments have to the ingredients.
<p>
Another example is called HE (High Energy) explosive.  Think solid rocket fuel.  Finding HE that is also not dangerous to carry
is difficult.  
<p>Plastique is find to carry, so is SEMTEC (actually a more potent, oderless, and probably tasteless plastique).  Rumor has it that Viet
Vets used C-4 plastique as sterno.  Don't know if I believe that, but I have 
heard from several reliable sources that the stuff is rather slow burning.  It
is when you can finally get it REAL hot or "concuss" it (as with a blasting
cap), that it finally goes nutsoid and makes the big bang.  Gladly I don't 
enough about it at that detail to say yay or nay to such claims.
<p>
Anyway, TNT, HE, SEMTEC and other exotics are found in various special devices 
like land mines, bomb warheads, tank shells, artillery shells, etc.  We won't
even go into such nasties as depleted uranium and HEAT rounds.  When terrorists
get their hands on that stuff, well it is truly war at that point.  Need a 
bunch of tanks and fighter bombers to counter that.
<p>
<h3>Summary</h3>
<p>
As you can see, this briefing didn't go into much detail.  Sorry if you were 
dissapointed,
but the goal was to give a brief description of the explosives in use
today by terrorists or other crazies.  The alarming
thing that should have gleaned from all this is that save the military stuff
(which probably can't be  controlled any better than they are being controlling 
now), it is easy for someone to pull together the ingredients to make a 
pretty deadly bomb.  Some inexperienced folk may blast themselves to little 
pieces trying to make even bigger bangs (and if no one else is close, that might not be so bad),
but to make really big bangs the crazy probably needs some sophisticated 
manufacturing facility.  The exception might be the fertilizer bomb, but
that is probably a special case (see notes on fertilizer bombs above) and hard
to hide.  A little better effort at peripheral security would probably have
prevented the deaths in Okalhoma.  A good security firm can probably tell
you what to do...think Beirut Marine Barracks and Oklahoma City, and you will
have saved yourself a lot of money paying a security firm!
<p>
Bomb manufacturing for mass destruction probably won't go undetected unless 
someone has a fairly large facility and no visitors.  Of course there are 
exceptions (time will certainly illustrate these exceptions), but for the most
part, it would be difficult to build a bomb to take out a major bridge without
someone noticing (or so we hope!).
<p>
On the other hand, a bomb to take out a car and its occupants can be made
in your kitchen, and a landmine probably in your garage with a drill press.
<p>
<p>
<h3>Building Safety</h3>
<p>
And finally, it should be noted that a little more attention to building
security in EVERY case of mass murder in an office complex could have saved
most of the lives lost.  Even the World Trade Center could have been avoided.
Large underground parking lots are setup up to take your money, not provide
security of any sort, let alone prevent large amounts of explosive to be
trucked in.  When is the last time you had your trunk viewed?  It doesn't have
to be an intrusive search...pop it open at an inspection point upon entering
an undergroudn parking lot, or if you need to get close to a large building, andthat should suffice.  
<p>
Too intrusive.  Bull.   Tell that to the parents of the children in the 
Oklahoma City Federal Building.  Double Bull!
<p>
Any company not concerned enough to limit access to physical proximity of
their building is just asking for a huge damage suit in the future.  And it
is really not all that hard to do if you have a bit of space next to your
building.
<p>
<p>
<h3>Political Statement</h3>
So rather than try to think up some way to stop the ingredients from being a
available (no more oven cleaner...now that is a disaster for spare rib lovers
out there!), we need to concentrate on the people factor.  In other words,
stop terrorists, not terrorist weapons.  
<p>
If you no longer have assault rifles, than people who want
to assault will use volatile gas bombs, pipe bombs, wall bombs, sachel charges,
stolen dynamite, or even large garbage cans of fertilizer, knives, bows and
arrows, bamboo stuffed with salt peter. <p>
Have you heard of what the IRA did with bombs in a country where there are less semi-automatics than there are in Los Angeles?
<p>
Get the message?  Anything can be made into a bomb.  Fortunatly, not everyone is prone to
doing so.  Let's concentrate on identifying those prone to doing such things, 
and watch 'em close.  When we detect them doing something strange (like buying 
200 lbs of fertilizer when they live in an apartment with no lawn), then we
watch 'em a little closer.
<p>
I like the idea of a convicted felon not being able to buy a weapon.  How about 
having to have a license to buy gasoline?  Sounds ludicrous doesn't it.  But
a can of gasoline is ten times more dangerous than an AK-47, and the bloke
doesn't even have to be there when he (or she) set it off to do the damage!
<p>
Moreover, if one looks at the information made available AFTER someone shoots 
a bunch of people up, you'll find that in most cases someone knew something
was wrong.  And where someone didn't percieve there was a problem...why that 
very same crazy could just as easily have built a homemade grenade!
<p>
And this briefing didn't go into chemical weapons that don't explode or have
a trigger!
What has been happening in Japanese train 
stations could easily be happening in the U.S..  Unfortunately chemical 
dispersant
weapons are not as hard to buy components for and are relatively much more
safer to build than explosives.
<p>
This is really an excellent example.  In Japan, people don't have guns.  
Mass murdereres there slice peoples throats or plant chemical weapons
killing bunches all at once if they don't want the personal touch. Stopping
the common bloke from owning a gun doesn't seem to help Japan control the
crazies any more than it would help curb them in the U.S..
<p>
<p>
