<HTML>
<title>MILNET:  Terrorism - Hijacking Chronology</title>
<center>
<img src="milnetsm.gif" align=middle, alt="Milnet">
<p>
<p>
<a href="milnet.htm"><img src="milico.gif" align=middle alt="Milnet Main"></a>
<a href="terror.htm"><img src="terror.gif" align=middle alt="Terrorism"></a>
<p>
<p></center>
<H1>A Chronology of Hijackings (1968-
1978)</H1>
1968:  In the Middle East, starting in 1968, PLO sympathizers hijacked an El Al (Israeli 
National Airline).  While getting lots of publicity, the  PLO  hijackers did not kill anyone.<P>
The Rome to Tel Aviv flight of TWA flight 840 was hijacked on 8/29/69, also with no one 
killed.  But this "non-violent" approach to hijacking was not to continue.<P>
9/16/70:  Five airliners were hijacked in unison by five separate attacking groups of PLO 
hijackers.    Sky Marshals   killed 1 hijacker, and disarmed one bomb.<P>
By1972, the hijack violence was on a meteoric rise.<P>
5/8/72:  A Belgian Sabina airliner was seized by hijackers with  guns .  One person killed, 4 
injured.  <P>
5/30/72:  22 days after the Sabina airliner was hijacked,  hijackers entered Lod Airport,  
grabbed an airliner on the ground and while fleeing the aircraft sprayed the airport lounge 
with machine guns killing 26  and injuring 76.<P>
An El Al airliner was attacked with a bomb in the luggage compartment, but by then El Al 
had armored the compartements on all their flights and no one was harmed.<P>
9/5/72:  In retaliation for this failure and an Israeli reprisal raid, the  Munich Massacre  was 
planned and carried out, the attack taking place at the Olympic village on the morning of 
9/5/72.<P>
10/72:  Lufthansa 615 was hijacked in October of '72 with no one being injured.<P>
4/73:  The USSR was not exempt from terrorist attacks as an Aeroflot airliner was hijacked 
by a bomb carrying hijacker in April of 1973.  The flight crew overcame the hijacker, and the 
hijacker and one crew member were killed when the bomb exploded.  <P>
7/20/73:  Three months later,  1 person was killed and 1 injured by explosion when a JAL 
airliner was hijacked.<P>
<P>
8/5/73:  A TWA airliner was hijacked to Athens, and while on the ground, 5 people were 
killed and 55 injured.<P>
12/73:  Four months later the same terrorist group hijacked a Lufthansa airliner, but 
fortunately no one was hurt.<P>
12/73:  But five days later, the Pan Am customs area was attacked, and a Pan Am airliner 
was taken over on the ground, with 30 people killed, and 28 injured.<P>
2/20/74:  An Air Vietnam airliner bomb in an aircharft carrying hijackers exploded the bomb 
in the air killing 3 and injuring 6 on Februrary 20, 1974.<P>
While other terrorist actions occurred, things calmed down on airliners...at least until ...<P>
6/03/75:   when 1 person was killed and 14 injured by a small bomb exploding and 
decompressing the aircraft, killing the would-be hijacker.<P>
6/27/76:  One of the most publicized airliner hijackings was the hijacking of  Air France flight 
139, an Airbus, by a  PLO  faction.  The aircraft had a very large number of Israelis on 
board, and when the aircraft finally landed at Entebbe Airport in Uganda, Israeli commandos 
went in and repatrioted the hostages.  Only four were killed, including the commando 
commander, Yani.  No hostage survived the rescue.<P>
7/2/76:  An Eastern Airlines aircraft suffered an explosion killing the hijacker.  No one else 
was killed.<P>
12/4/77:  Malaysian Airlines suffered their worse tragedy when an aircraft was hijacked and 
when the crew tried to overpower the hijacker, an explosion killed the aircrew and the aircraft 
crashed immediately killing all 93 on board.<P>
8/18/78:  Another Phillipines Airlines hijacker was killed by his bomb, injuring a crew member 
and two passengers.<P>
An El Al crewbus was hijacked while transporting the crew to an aircraft, 1 killed, 1 
injured.<P>
By the end of 1979, actual hijackings began to slow down with perhaps only 1 a year.<P>
But in areas where tensions remain, hijackings occur with alarming regularity...i.e.  Shiite 
Muslim  extremists hijacked a TWA airliner and forced it to land at Beirut airport (in 
Lebanon), and killed a U.S. Navy sailor.  <P>
Hijackings began to taper off as Islamic groups began to use other, more successful means 
to deliver their message.  Incidents at airports and against airliners on the ground have also 
occurred.<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
