<TITLE>OneStep Internet Services Provider Services - IP Primer</TITLE>
<p><center>
	            <img src="1steplog.gif">
<p>
<p>
 		                  <a href="onestep.htm"><img src="puzzle.gif"></a>
<p>
</center><H1>OneStep Internet Services Provider Services - Do Your Own NT 
</h1>
<p>
Okay, its not that tough.  An IP address is nothing more than 4 sets of numbers,kind of like your telephone area code, prefix and last four digits.  In this case however we use a speical notation to write them down.  This is usually called an octet.  Here is what one looks like:
<p>
<center>
<img src="blumrbt4.gif">
</center>
<p>
IP Octets are created by a network administrator.  The admin type is tasked with choosing the addresses from a pool handed over for his or her administration by an organization known as the NIC.  In truth however, the IP address has grown into a larger than life element of something called Domain Name Services.  So really, the NIC hands out a domain name, and establishes an IP address range for that domain.  What's a domain...just a range of IP addresses.  Simple.  
<p>
There are three kinds of Domains that used to available, a class A (like having your own 800 number and all those digits behind it!), a class B (like having all the numbers in your prefix), and a class C (like having say a third of all the numbers in the last four digits of your phone number.
<p>
Using the standard IP octed, here is how you can view the three classes:
<p><center>
<img src="ipclass.gif">
<p></center>
So you might be assigned an IP address of 203.190.112.143.  Your office mate might be assigned 203.190.112.46.  If everyone in your building has a 203.190.112 as the first three numbers in the octet, then chances are your building (at least) has been assigned a class C domain.
<p>
<h2>URLs</h2>
<p>
URLs are nothing more than a symbolic reference that will take a web user to a new page or a new place on the same page.  See the URL primer</a> for more info.
<p>
We mention them here, cuz often inside a URL is a domain name...i.e. www.onestep.com, is a domain with WWW tacked on the front.  If you wanted to go to see the onestep WWW home page, you'd use the URL of "http://www.onestep.com/".  Obviously you know now tha the onestep.com is really an IP address (205.185.9.42 at the writing of this document).  The WWW tells us the URL is for the home page of a server, and the "http" tells us the kind of TCP/IP service we should be looking for.  In this case, "http" stands for the protocol that delivers WEB pages across the Internet.
<p>
So there you have it...IP addresses, Domains, and URLs...all in one swell fwoop!

<p>
<hr>
<address>onestep@onestep.com</address>

