<HTML>
<TITLE>OneStep Internet Services Provider Services - Do It Yourself: Layout</TITLE>
<p><center>
	         <img src="1steplog.gif">
<p>
<p>
 		                <a href="initial.htm"><img src="1stepico.gif"></a> 
 

<H1>OneStep Internet Services Provider Services 
<p>
</center>
Do It Yourself:  Layout</h1>
<p>
The best idea we've seen for creating a layout of your web pages comes from software engineers who, thinking of themselves as artists, copied an idea from Hollywood.  
<p>
<p>
<center>			<img src="pages.gif">
</center>
<h2>Storyboards</h2>
<p>
The idea is nothing more than just taking a sheaf of papers and roughly sketching out what you want your heirarchy to look like.  Each page represents a level of the heirarchy...usually themselves comprised of text and graphics that represent a particular subject or group of topics.  This is very much like the storyboard process used in hollywood to figure out scenes flows from one to another, establishing transistion points as well as "forks" in the plot.
<p>
Your web pages are not much different.  To start yourself out, try just putting down headings and wavy lines for the text that goes in place under them.  Draw a square for each graphic you want to use.  Later we will size them to fit better, but for now just note their existence and roughly where they should go on the page.
<p>
Once you have your pages laid out (and you don't have to lay out all of them, perhaps just a few layers, from the home page down the links to say two or three layers), then its time to think about how your going to link them.  
<p>
<P>
<center>			<img src="trans.gif">
</center>
<H2>Transitions</h2>
Just like in good literature or a decent movie, your transitions must "hook" the reader into reading further.  Fortunately, html and web browsers help a lot by underlining and coloring the link text blue for you.  Doesn't take a rocket scientist to figure out how to move to a new topic in the World Wide Web.  But you are the one now trying to guide your target user to the message you want to deliver.
<p>
In your storyboards, you laid out subjects that led from the home page down through a heirarchy, to the last pages.  This heirarchy probably represents a heirarchy of topics...subjects of interest to your target user.  Now you just figure out a keyword that will be highlighted by the linking process, a keyword that your target user will intuitively understand leads to the message you have prepared.  Sounds difficult?  Nonsense.  Look at the previous pages in this tutorial heirarchy.   
<p>
We started from creating a home page down into the basic topics needed to make you a pro at creating your web pages.  
<p>
And if you find that the keyword used today is not right tomorrow, simply change it.  The html system makes this easy to do with no fuss.
<p>

</DOC>
