<HTML>
<TITLE>MILNET:  Military Information - The Boland Amendment</TITLE>
<center>
<img align=middle src="milnetsm.gif" alt="Milnet">
<p>
<p>
<a href="milnet.htm"><img alt="Milnet Main" align=middle src="milico.gif"></a>
<a href="intell.htm"><img alt="Intell" align=middle src="intell.gif"></a>
<p>
<B><H1>The Boland Amendment</H1>
<p>
</center>
</B>Passed on December 8, 1982, this amendment to the  War Powers  Act 
of 1973, states that U.S. Agencies are prohibited from providing 
military equipment, training or support to anyone "for the purpose of 
overthrowing the Government of Nicaragua."  <P>
The literal purpose was to prevent any CIA funds or support to go to the 
Sadinista (rebels fighting against the communist Nicaraguan government).  
Congress felt this was necessary because the Reagan administration had 
pledged to support the Sadinistas in their battle for freedom for their 
country.  Unfortunately a very left leaning Democratic Congress 
prohibited the administration from continuing funding to support the 
Sandinistas at a critical time.  As it became evident this was a 
mistake, Congress repealed the Amendment and re-instituted the funding.  
Eventually the U.S. and Sandinista pressure resulted in democratic 
elections in Nicaragua.<P>
The actual wording of the Amendment was interpreted to disallow only 
U.S. Intelligence Agencies, thus allowing members of the staff of the 
NSC (which is not an Intelligence Agency of the U.S. government) to 
route funds to the Sandinistas.  A angry democratic Congress responded 
by attempting to prosecute Col. Oliver North, Adm. John Poindexter and 
others in a set of public hearings.  North was convicted on a number of 
charges but finally exonerated of all but a minor infraction, Adm. John 
Poindextor (ret'd) was convicted of lieing to Congress.  <P>
<p>
See also <a href="presdir.htm">Presidential Directive</a> of 1976, or <a href="i
ntauth.htm">Intelligence
Authorization</a> Act of 1981, the <a href="warpower.htm">War Powers</a> Act of
1973, or the <a href="hughes.htm">The Hughes-Ryan Act</a>.<P>
<P>

</HTML>
