<TITLE>MILNET:  Intelligence - COMINT Definition</TITLE>
<center>
<img align=middle src="milnetsm.gif" alt="Milnet">
<p>
<p>
<a href="milnet.htm"><img alt="Milnet Main" align=middle src="milico.gif"></a>
<a href="intell.htm"><img alt="Intell" align=middle src="intell.gif"></a>
<p>
<p>
<H1>Intelligence:  COMINT Definition</h1>
<p></center>
COMINT is defined as the collection of communications intelligence.  This is more accurately defined as the collection of information pertaining to the patterns of, the codes used in, the frequencies used, and the sites used for communications.  Thus COMINT is the collection of information about the target's communications capabilities and procedures.  

Typically COMINT is gathered by ground sites who are able to "listen-in" on the target's communications wether it be by radio, telegraph, telephone, television, or even laser.  Recently the Clinton administration urged adoption of the "Clipper Chip" encryption technology to aid commercial and financial uses of digital communictions in securing data, but at the same time allowing authorized agencies such as law enforcement, FBI, and NSA to easily decrypt encoded messages.  The controversy has been going on since the Bush Administration.

There are, of course, a number of different methods for collecting COMINT besides from a ground station, the most notable two being the collection via aircraft or satellite, known as   <a href="/milnet/overhead.htm">overhead reconaissance</a>. 
<p>
