<html>
<title>MILNET:  C3I Database</title>
<center>
<img src="milnetsm.gif" align=middle, alt="Milnet">
<p>
<p>
<a href="milnet.htm"><img src="milico.gif" align=middle alt="Milnet Main"></a>
<a href="military.htm"><img src="miltico.gif" align=middle alt="Military"></a>
<p>
<h1>C3I Database, 1990</h1>
</center>
<p>
The database below is based upon declassified information available to the
defense industry just prior to the start of the Gulf War.  Some of the programs
listed in the database have been completed (with little or no fan fare as is the custom with those programs whose original IOC dates were classified or subject
of dis-information).
Others may have been cancelled and replaced with funding from other undisclosed
funding.  In any case, this should give you an indication of the kinds of systems, and 
upgrades the U.S. has made in the key area of Command, Control, Communications,
and Intelligence.
<p>
<a name="SDI">
<h2>Satellite Reconnaissance </h2>
The major emphasis in U.S. funded programs over the last 6 years (1985 through 1990) has been on Strategic Modernization, plus 
the surveillance components of <b>SDI</b> and ADI (Air Defense Initiative) 
programs. <P>
[Editor's Note:  It is interesting to note that in 1995, the choice of 
beefing up surveillance appears to be an excellent decision...what with the
increasing lack of funds for other purposes, it appears that the military
establishment is in excellent position to watch outside U.S. borders as well
as their allies borders.  In a long period of isolationism (which we appear
to be in), surveillance is an excellent tool to keep small fires from becoming
major damaging fires due to a lack of discovery.]
<p>
<pre>

</pre>
<h2>Umbrella Surveillance Programs</h2><P>

<dl>
<dt><B>ADI</B>	      <dd>Air Defense Initiative.  Tasks include the defense of              
the U.S. from Air and Space Attack. A large portion of the             
management and <b>C3I</b> tasks will be developed under the <b>SDI</b>             
umbrella of programs (see below), in a consolidated project combining the 
<b>SDI</b> and <b>ADI BM/C3</b> system development at the Air Force's Electronic 
Systems Division.  Some of the other projects included in <b>ADI</b> are:<P>
<UL>
<LI><B>ADISC2:</B> ADI Simulation for Command and Control<BR>
<li><B>AOTH-R:</B> Advanced Over-The-Horizon Radar                  <BR>
<li><B>ASTS:</B>   Advanced Surveillance and Tracking System                  <BR>
<li><B>SBR: </B>   Space Based Radar system 
</UL>
<P>
             Experiments which led to technology used in these systems             
are:<P>
<UL>
<LI>                 <B>APAR:</B>   Airborne Phased Array Radar       
<li><B>AST:</B>    
Atmospheric Surveillance Technology (FY85)                 
<li><B>CMSP:</B>   Cruise Missile 
Surveillance Program
</UL>
<p>
<p>
<dt>                <B>SDI-SATKA</B>	<dd><b>SDI</b> Surveillance, Acquisition, 
Tracking, and              Kill Assessment) one of five major programs 
in             the Strategic Defense System (<b>SDS</b>).  This program             
is the largest single program in the strategic             surveillance 
market segment.  Represents over half             of the total funding 
for strategic surveillance.             Experiments  for <b>SDI</b >are being 
performed to             characterize a number of targets under a number 
of             background environments. Funded <B>SDI-SITKA</B> programs 
are:<P>
<UL>
<LI> <B>BSTS:</B>   Boost Surveillance and Tracking System               <BR>
<li><B>GSTS:</B>   Ground-based Surveillance and Tracking System               <BR>
<li><B>SSTS:</B>   Space Surveillance and Tracking System               <BR>
<li><B>SBI:</B>    Space Based Interceptor               <BR>
<li><B>ERIS: </B>  Exoatmospheric Reentry vehicle Interceptor System
</UL>
<P>
<P>
            In addition there are a number of projects centered             
around the battle managment and <b>C3I</b> capabilities of the <b>SDS</b>, 
for example:<P>
<P>
<UL>
<LI><b>CC/SOIF:</B> Command Center/System Operation and Integration Functions               
<BR>
<li><B>NTB:</B>     National Test Bed             
</UL>
</dl>
<P>
<pre>


</pre>

<H1>Individual Surveillance Program 
Descriptions</H1>
<P>
<dt><B>BSTS</B>	      <dd>Boost Surveillance and Tracking System being              
developed under <B>SDI</B> encompasses a super set              of the 
<B>DSP</B> program and eventually will              provide the function 
<B>DSP</B> provides today.               The goal is to fully prove out 
<B>BSTS</B> before              discarding <B>DSP</B>.  Full scale 
<B>BSTS</B> development              will be initiated in 1990.      
<BR>
<p>
<dt><B>CONUS-OTH</B>	<dd>Continental US Over The Horizon radar              
program will continue through to completion              of the East 
Coast radar unit, and the              construction of other new radars, 
with              budget pressures causing stretched program              
schedules.    <B>DSP</B>	      Defense Support Program, long range 
future              based upon advanced technology in space              
borne surveillance systems, and specifically              tied to the 
success of the <B>BSTS</B> program,              with <B>DSP</B> 
providing the functionality until              BSTS is fully 
operational.   <BR>
<p>
<dt><B>GPS</B> 	      <dd>Global Positioning System, part of the <B>NAVSTAR</B> 
system             which provides position, altitude and time data to             
special ground receivers.  Mentioned here because GPS is             
reported to also carry a Nuclear Detonation Detection              
system (<B>NUDET</B>).   <B>JSS</B>	      Joint Surveillance System 
program, 48              minimally attended radar systems (<B>MARS</B>) 
are              planned to replace existing <B>JSS</B> radars.               
Jointly funded by the FAA under the FAA              National Airspace 
System program.<BR>
<p>
<dt><B>NUDET</B>	      <dd>Nuclear Detection System (NDS) is expected              
to be continued in full procurement and              deployment as paced 
by the GPS program which              <B>NUDET</B> rides on.
<p>
<dt><B>NWS</B>	     <dd>North Warning System program to continue the              
modernization and replacement of the present              <B>DEW</B> 
line system.  FY 1990 is the peak              funding period and will 
support the              deployment of Short Range Radars.    <BR>
<p>
<B>SDI</B>	      <dd>Strategic Defense Initiative will be budget limited as              
both political and world events lead to an overall             reduction 
in budgets.  <B>SDI</B> is comprised of the Strategic             
Defense System (<B>SDS</B>) and involves detection of incoming              
ballistic missiles in either the boost phase, midcourse             
correction phase, or in the terminal phase of launch.               
Elimination of incoming warheads can be accomplished             in any 
of the three phases, the earlier the better.  See             <B>SDI-
SITKA</B> above.  The battle management/C3 portion of <B>SDI</B>             
will be integrated into the <B>WWMCCS</B> systems in place today.             
(See <B>WWMCCS</B>).    <BR>
<p>
<dt><B>SRS</B>	      <dd>Surveillance Radar Stations program will              
also cover the area around Iceland, and will              provide a new 
Command and Control Center as              well as continued acquisition 
and deployment              of radars for the Caribbean Basin Radar              
Network (<B>CBRN</B>).<br>

<p>
<dt><B>SRT</B>	      <dd>Strategic Relocatable Targets program is an              
effort to detect, identify, and target              mobile Soviet 
strategic missile launchers              and associated mobile command 
centers. Will              apply advanced signal and data processing              
technology, data fusion, and artificial              intelligence 
techniques to sensor data              derived from other programs.<P>
<p>
</dl>
<p>
<pre>


</pre>
<H2>Major Strategic Command and Control 
Elements    </H2>
<p>
Small projection of growth, probably not enough to keep up  
with inflation.  FY1989 reached a level of $865 million.   This 
segment is further divided up into:    -  SDI Systems and Battle 
Management program  -  Everything else.    The rest of the 
programs in this segment deal with major  operational strategic 
command and control elements and are  fairly mature. </H2>
<P>
<pre>
</pre>
<H2>Strategic Command and Control Programs    
</H2>
<dt><B>WWMCCS</B>	<dd>Worldwide Military Command and Control              
System.  Shift of program management back to              DCA will 
revise plans for completion of the              <B>WWMCCS</B> 
Information System (WIS).  The plan              is for procurement of 
new computers to              replace the older mainfames currently 
being              used.  The revised plan and reduction in              
spending expected will push out procurements              into FY 1992. 
<B>WWMCCS</B> includes the following: <P>
<UL>
<LI><b>ABCP</B>:   Airborne Command Post aircraft               <BR>
<li><B>CCPDS</B>:  Command Center Processing and Display System                <BR>
<li><B>CSSR</B>:   Communications System Segment Replacement               <BR>
<li><B>CUP</B>:    Common User Package (runs on IBM PC3270s)              <BR>
<li><B>NCMC</B>:   NORAD Cheyene Mountain Complex               <BR>
<li><B>NMCS</B>:   National Military Command System (WWMCCS Core)               <BR>
<li><B>SACWPS</B>: SAC War Planning System                 <BR>
<li><B>SCIS</B>:   Survivable Communications Integration System               <BR>
<li><B>SDME</B>:   Software Development and Maintenance Environment               <BR>
<li><B>SPADOC</B>: Space Defense Operations Center               <BR>
<li><B>WAM</B>:    WWMCCS ADP Modernization program (formerly WIS)               <BR>
<li><B>WIN</B>:    WWMCCS Intercomputer Network               <BR>
<li><B>WISWS</B>:  WIS (now WAM) Workstation Segment (uses POSIX  compliant UNIX on 
Apple Mac IIx computers)   
</UL>
</dl>
<pre>


</pre>
<H2>Strategic C3 Program Details</H2>
<dl>
<dt><B>ABCP</B>        <dd>Airborne Command Post aircraft, consists of a fleet 
of              24 EC-135 aircraft used by the major commands, there               
always being a responsible commander airborne for each              
major command.  The current updages are interim changes              
while DOD and Congress try to decide when to replace               aging 
EC-135 aircraft. The replacement has been further               delayed 
and that portion of the program is not expected               to start 
until FY 1992.<P>
<dt><B>CCPDS</B>       <dd>Command Center Processing and Display System.  
Consists              of dedicated computers, software, displays, and 
consoles               at the <B>NCMC</B>, the <B>NMCC</B> in the 
Pentagon, the alternate <B>NMCC</B>              (<B>ANMCC</B>), and the 
HQ SAC Command Post.  <B>CCPDS</B> provides for              reception 
and processing of ballistic missile TW/AA              information.<P>
<dt><B>NCMC</B>        <dd><B>NORAD</B> Cheyenne Mountain Complex.  This 
underground               facility (inside Cheyenne Mountain) that 
serves the               combined needs of <B>NORAD</B>, <B>ADCOM</B>, 
Air Force Space Command,              the U.S. Space Command.  It is a 
central place for              the gathering and display of strategic 
surveillance and              warning information, and as such, is a 
major surveillance              data fusion center.<P>
<dt><B>NMCS</B>         <dd>National Military Command System.  Tied to the 
National              Command Authority (President, Secretary of 
Defense, etc)              Central Core of the <B>WWMCCS</B>.  The 
<B>NMCS</B> consists of the              National Command Centers 
(<B>NCMC</B>, Alternate <B>NCMC</B>, and the              National 
Emergency Airborne Command Post), the              communications that 
link them to intelligence systems,              and other subordinate 
command centers.  The centers               receive warning information 
on potential or actual               hostile action, friendly and enemy 
force status, and              crisis or contingency situation 
information.<P>
<dt><B>SWPS</B>         <dd>Strategic War Planning System.  Supports development 
of               the Strategic Mission Data Preparation System 
(<B>SMDPS</B>) at              SAC Headquarters, Offutt AFB, Nebraska.  
<P>
<dt><B>SPADOC</B>       <dd>Space Defense Operations Center.  Expands the space 
role of the NCMC.  <B>SPADOC</B> is a key element of 
<B>SPADCCS</B>.  A              number of centers with <B>NCMC</B> 
currently support <B>SPADOC</B>               (<B>NCMC</B> and CSOC).  
The <B>SPADOC</B> development will provide               the central 
command and control facility at the <B>NCMC</B> and              the 
integration of the related elements that functionally              
comprise the <B>SPADCCS</B>.  For assessment and warning, all              
of the resources of space surveillance, such as              Spacetrack, 
the DSP satellites, <B>GEODSS</B>, <B>NAVSPASUR</B>, and              
other sensors and intelligence sources, feed data to               
<B>SPADOC</B>.  <B>SPADOC's</B> stated mission is to manage the space              
defense weapons, conrol of engagement operations, and               
evaluation of engagements.  Mission support functions              
include the resources needed for orbit and trajectory               
computations, communications and data processing support.  <P>
<P>
</dl>
<pre>


</pre>

<H2>Strategic Communications Programs 
</H2>
 Strategic communications provide command and control of  nuclear forces 
under wartime conditions, thus must survive  repeated nuclear attack and 
the environmentals associated  with post-nuclear attack.    This 
includes both atmospheric post-attack conditions as  well as hardness 
during the actual attack and ecompasses  various transmission techniques 
across a widely separated  number of frequencies.<P>
 <P>
</H2>
<dl>
<dt><B>ELF</B>     	<dd>Extra Low Frequency communications systems              
is being deployed and have achieved              operational capability.  
No new funding is              expected.   <BR>
<dt><B>GWEN</B>	      <dd>Ground Wave Emergency Network project's              
<B>MEECN</B> program will be carried through its              third 
phase with some stretchout in the              program.    <BR>
<p>
<dt><B>MILSTAR</B>	<dd>Military Strategic Tracking and Relay              
satellite program is the most sophisticated              and expensive 
satellite communications              program ever undertaken.  The 
program is              moving towards the initial launch of the              
first vehicle.  Although there continues a              great deal of 
Congressional support for the              project, there will 
undoubtedly be some              stretchout of the deployment schedule.  
The              Air Force Terminal portion of the program              
went into limited production in FY 1989 and              is expected to 
continue to recieve strong              support.  Aside from the 
satellite systems development             there are four programs being 
funded or considered:<P>
<UL>
<LI><b>AFT</B>:    Air Force Terminal               <BR>
<li><B>LVT</B>:    Low Volume Terminal                <BR>
<li><B>MAFT</B>:   Minature Air Force Terminal                <BR>
<li><B>PAFT</B>:   Portable Air Force Terminal 
</ul>
<p>
Note:  Data from 1990.
<p>
<dt><B>SLC</B>	      <dd>Submarine Laser Communications program is              
expected only to be funded for limited              technology 
development and system studies              during the tight budget 
periods expected.<P>
</dl>

<P>
<pre>


</pre>

 <B>Tactical Reconnaissance and Surveillance  </B>  <P>
Although a slight decrease in funding is expected in FY 1990  and FY 
1991, there will be a substantial upswing in three  years.  This funding 
will be for <B>ATARS</B>, <B>JSTARS</B>, and <B>UAVs</B>, as  well as 
improvements to sytems to achieve greater range and  area of coverage.   
<P>
<P>
<dl>
<dt><B>ACCS</B>	      <dd>Army Command and Control System will              
continue to procure NDI equipment in order              to minimize 
program costs and speed the              introduction  of new comercial 
computer              technology into fieldable military systems.               
A new major focus will be in software              development and 
integration.    
<dt><B>ADDS</B>       	<dd>Army Data Distribution System will 
be              constrained by overall budget pressures.    <BR>
<dt><B>AFACS</B>	      <dd>Air Force Advanced Communications System              
will support the procurement of HAVE QUICK              II radio 
modifications and the airbrone              SINCGARS radio.    <BR>
<dt><B>AFC3AD</B>	<dd>Air Force C3 Advanced Development program is              
expected to continue in the future on a              level of effort 
basis.      <BR>
<dt><B>AFTACS</B>	<dd>Air Force Tactical Air Control System              
program will be stretched, as the central              element (joint 
development of the Marine              Corps TOAM program).    <BR>
<dt><B>AFTADS</B>	<dd>Advanced Field Artillery Tactical Data              
System program will be delayed in fielding              due to the fact 
that the already validated              software will not run on the 
current Common              Hardware/Software (CHS) computers that are              
part of ACCS.    <BR>
<dt><B>ATARS</B>	      <dd>Advanced Tactical Air Reconnaissance System              
will take advantage of advances in              electrooptical and 
microelectronics              technology.  Near real time, direct 
readout              of mission data will be the results of this              
investment, both in manned and unmanned              airborne platforms.    
<dt><B>ATSA</B>	      <dd>Advanced Tactical Support Aircraft (US              
Navy), low funding level for a combined              ocean surveillance, 
air surveillance, and EW              surveillance missions of current 
Navy              aircraft (S-3, E-2C and EA-6B respectively).    <BR>
<dt><B>ATSS</B>	     <dd> Advanced Tactical Surveillance System.    <BR>
<dt><B>AWACS</B>	      <dd>Airborne Warning and Control System (Air              
Force E-3 Sentry) will continue to grow and              will comprise a 
significant amount of the              this market segments funding.  FY 
1989 saw              an increase for new radar improvement              
programs and the Air Force will be              supporting a follow on 
version of this              aircraft.    <BR>
<dt><B>FAAD C2</B>	<dd>Unknown Acronym, will continue funding but              
with moderate growth despite a sharp              increase in the FY 
1988 budget.    <BR>
<dt><B>JSTARS</B>	<dd>Joint Surveillance and Target Attack Radar              
System has begun testing under full-scale              development.  
There are concerns over the              survivability of the E-8 
aircraft though.               Production decision was expected in FY 
1991              with the procurement funding to occur in FY              
1992, but events in the Middle East moved the 		delivery of the 
first two operational aircraft  		built from the test aircraft 
to be delivered in 		in time for key usage during Operation 
Desert 		helping distinguish friendly ground vehicles  	
	as well as was a key element in the "SCUD Hunt".   <BR>
<dt><B>JSIPS</B>	      <dd>Joint Services Imagery Processing System.               
No details, but the Marine Corps is              participating with the 
Air Force and is              expected to continue funding.    <BR>
<dt><B>JTF</B>	      <dd>Joint Tactical Fusion projects of the Navy,  <B>            
</B>Air Force, and Army will combine the data              from various 
sensors and types of data to              battlefield commanders as well 
as strategic              planners with verified accurate data on the              
battlefield and conditions.  Major              procurement and 
deployment expected in the              1990s.    <BR>
<dt><B>JTC3</B>	      <dd>Joint Tactical C3 Agency program is expected              
to continue although slightly reduced.    <BR>
<dt><B>LRAACA</B>	<dd>P-3C Update IV program, should generate near              
term funding.    <BR>
<dt><B>MACC&amp C</B>	<dd>MAC Command and Control System, a 158 node              
Information Processing System, will reach              peak funding in 
FY 1991 and additional              funding will continue. <BR>
<dt><B>MCS</B>	      <dd>Maneuver Control System is declining until              
FY 1992, when <B>CHS</B> computers will be              introduced into 
this area.    <B>NTC</B>	      Navy Tactical Reconnaissance will 
provide              upgrades to the E-2C, P-3C and S-3 aircraft              
and thus can expect to sustain a significant              level of 
funding.    <BR>
<dt><B>ROTH</B>	      <dd>Relocatable Over The Horizon radar program              
is expected to continue through development              and 
procurement, intended to implement the              Navy's Tactical Wide 
Area Surveillance              (<B>TWAS</B>)    <BR>
<dt><B>SMMN</B>	      <dd>Secure Multi-Media Network technology              
program.    <B>TAOM</B>	      Tactical Air Operations Module (US Marine 
Corps). <BR>
<B>TAR</B>	      <dd>Tactical Air Reconnaissance (US Navy)              
program is expected to provide a modest              level of support 
for F/A-18 sensor pods.               Navy is expected to allocate 
increased              funding as the Air Force <B>ATARS</B> program 
nears              completion of development and evaluation.    <BR>
<dt><B>TRIGS	TR-1 </B> <dd>Ground System and advanced development              
of side-looking airborne radar is expected              to receive wide 
support.    <B>UAV</B>	      Unmanned Aerial Vehicle program is              
continuing with strong support with there              now being 
families of <B>UAVs</B> (short range,              medium range, and 
long endurance air              vehicles).  Questions remain as to 
mission              capabilities, operational concepts, and              
logistics support, and these must be              resolved before 
widespread application.               Expectations are for significant 
growth and              when issues are resolved, a rapid production              
and deployment will follow among all the              services.  <P>
</dl>
<pre>


</pre>
<h3>Tactical Communications</h3> <P>
The tactical communications systems market segment carries  about $2.3 
billion in FY 1989.    <P>
<dl>
<dt><B>EPLRS</B>      	<dd>Unknown acronym    <BR>
<dt><B>FLTSATCOM</B>	<dd>Fleet Sattellite Communications program will              
decline as only UHF Follow On (<B>UFO</B>) projects              for 
upgrading the current on orbit systems.              Navy is progressing 
with development and              production of EHF terminals and 
funding for              that portion of <B>FLTSATCOM</B> is expected to              
increase substantially in the FY 1991 and              beyond.    <BR>
<dt><B>JTIDS</B>	      <dd>Joint Tactical Intelligence Data System will              
continue to enjoy strong funding.    <BR>
<dt><B>MIDS</B>	      <dd>Nato Multifunctional Information              
Distribution System will add to the <B>JTIDS</B>              program 
funding.    <BR>
<dt><B>MSE</B>	      <dd>Mobile Suscriber Equipment program, over              
$1.0 billion in funding - Joint U.S./French procurement, 
the last major buy under the              <B>TRI-TAC</B> program, and 
thus after this funding is complete the expectations are 
for a major  decline.<BR>
<dt><B>SCOTT EHF</B>	<dd>Army Mobile Ground Forces EHF communications
for use with the <B>MILSTAR</B> program assets.               Production 
to take place in FY 1990.    <BR>
<dt><B>SINCGARS</B>	<dd>Unknown acronym.  Budget pressures will              
result in production stretchout, but funding              will remain 
strong.   <P>
</dl>
<P>
<pre>


</pre>

<B>Defense Wide Systems  </B>  <P>
Defense wide programs will be on a decline throughout FY  1990, but it 
is expected that the $2.3 billion market will  rise sharply in a few 
years, but still not sufficient to  offset continued mild inflation.<P>
<dl>
<dt><B>ARTS</B>       	<dd>Automated Remote Tracking Stations provides              
modernized tracking stations for programs              such as MILSTAR 
and will see funding for EHF <BR>
<dt><B>DCS</B>	      <dd>Defense Communications System funding              
dropping due to the costs driven by a need              to make the 
system survivable and resilient              in a wartime environment.    
<BR>
<dt><B>DDN</B>	      <dd>Defense Data Network met with a major delay              
in January of 1988, and still no word as to              its fate. <BR>
<dt><B>DMSP</B>	      <dd>Defense Meteorlogical Satellite Program to              
continue far into the future but rather than              a Block 6 
satellite, modifications will be              required to be made upon 
the Block 5D-3              satellites.    <BR>
<dt><B>DSCS</B>	      <dd>Defense Satellite Communications System will              
remain the principal wideband communications              system 
servicing the Tri-Service needs.  The              loss of U.S. space 
launch capability has              delayed the transition to full 
<B>DSCSIII</B>              operational capability until about 1991.  FY              
1990 and FY 1991 funding will decline with              <B>DSCSIII</B> 
satellites being placed in inventory              against contracts.  
This will further delay              any follow-on to the <B>DSCSIII</B> 
to late in FY              1992.   <BR>
<dt><B>DSN</B>	      <dd>Defense Switched Network will gradually              
replace <B>AUTOVON</B>.    <BR>
<dt><B>GPS</B>    	<dd>Global Positioning System is planned to              
reach full operatational capability in 1991.               The block 2R 
satellites funding will be              initiated in 1990 with 
significant build up              in FY 1991 and beyond.  Second source              
procurement should help increase a spread of              this funding 
to other primes.    <BR>
<dt><B>TT&amp C</B>       <dd>(Telemetry, Tracking &amp  Control)              
capability.     <P>
<P>
</dl>
